{"title_page": "And the Band Played On (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = And the Band Played On\n| image                = And The Band Played On Film Poster.jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Promotional poster\n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[And the Band Played On|And the Band Played On: Politics, People, and the AIDS Epidemic]]''|[[Randy Shilts]]}}\n| screenplay           = [[Arnold Schulman]]\n| director             = [[Roger Spottiswoode]]\n| starring             = {{unbulleted list|[[Matthew Modine]]|[[Alan Alda]]|[[Ian McKellen]]|[[Lily Tomlin]]|[[Richard Gere]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Carter Burwell]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = {{unbulleted list|Sarah Pillsbury|Midge Sanford}}\n| editor               = Lois Freeman-Fox\n| cinematography       = [[Paul Elliott (cinematographer)|Paul Elliott]]\n| runtime              = 141 minutes\n| company              = [[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = [[HBO]]\n| network              = HBO<br />[[NBC]]\n| budget               = $8 million\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1993|9|11}} \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''And the Band Played On''''' is a 1993 American [[television film]] [[docudrama]] directed by [[Roger Spottiswoode]]. The [[screenplay|teleplay]] by [[Arnold Schulman]] is based on the best-selling 1987 non-fiction book ''[[And the Band Played On|And the Band Played On: Politics, People, and the AIDS Epidemic]]'' by [[Randy Shilts]].\n\nThe film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]] before being broadcast by [[HBO]] on September 11, 1993. It later was released in the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Spain]], [[Germany]], [[Argentina]], [[Austria]], [[Italy]], [[Sweden]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Denmark]], [[New Zealand]], and [[Australia]]. The HBO movie was later aired on [[NBC]] in 1994. NBC (as well as [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]) were some of the networks considered to make a miniseries based on the book in the late 1980s, but the networks turned it down because they could not find a way to structure it as a two-night, four-hour miniseries. In 1994, NBC finally aired the movie with a parental discretion warning due to its sensitive subject matter.\n\n==Plot==\nIn a prologue set in 1976, American [[epidemiology|epidemiologist]] [[Don Francis]] arrives in a village on the banks of the [[Ebola River]] in [[Zaire]] and discovers many of the residents and the doctor working with them have died from a mysterious illness later identified as [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola hemorrhagic fever]]. It is his first exposure to such an [[epidemic]], and the images of the dead he helps [[cremation|cremate]] will haunt him when he later becomes involved with [[HIV/AIDS]] research at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].\n\nIn 1981, Francis becomes aware of a growing number of deaths from unexplained sources among [[gay]] men in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]] and [[San Francisco]], and is prompted to begin an in-depth investigation of the possible causes. Working with no money, limited space, and outdated equipment, he comes in contact with politicians, numerous members of the medical community (many of whom resent his involvement because of their personal agendas), and gay activists. Of the latter, some such as [[Bill Kraus]] support him, while others express resentment at what they see as unwanted interference in their lifestyles, especially in his attempts to close the local [[Gay bathhouse|bathhouses]]. One day, when exercising at a local gym, Kraus notices a spot at the base of his leg, worrying that it might be [[Kaposi's sarcoma]]. After a series of blood tests, Kraus is horrified that his worst fears have been confirmed when he learns that he has been diagnosed with AIDS. While Francis pursues his theory that AIDS is caused by a [[sexually transmitted infection|sexually transmitted virus]] on the model of [[feline leukemia virus|feline leukemia]], he finds his efforts are stonewalled by the CDC, which is unwilling to prove the disease is transmitted through blood, and competing [[France|French]] and [[United States|American]] scientists, particularly [[Robert Gallo|Dr. Robert Gallo]]. These medical researchers squabble about who should receive credit for discovering the virus. Meanwhile, the death toll climbs rapidly.\n\n==Principal cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Matthew Modine]] as [[Don Francis|Dr. Don Francis]], an epidemiologist, [[HIV/AIDS]] researcher, and one of the first scientists to suggest that AIDS was caused by an [[Pathogen|infectious agent]]\n* [[Alan Alda]] as [[Robert Gallo|Dr. Robert Gallo]], a biomedical researcher and one of the discoverers of HIV as the infectious agent responsible for [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]]\n* [[Ian McKellen]] as [[Bill Kraus]], a [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]] and AIDS activist and congressional aide\n* [[Glenne Headly]] as [[Mary Guinan|Dr. Mary Guinan]], an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]\n* [[Richard Masur]] as [[William Darrow|Dr. William Darrow]], one of the discoverers of HIV as the virus that causes AIDS\n* [[Saul Rubinek]] as Dr. James Curran, an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the CDC\n* [[Lily Tomlin]] as [[Selma Dritz|Dr. Selma Dritz]], a physician and epidemiologist\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]] as [[Ga\u00ebtan Dugas]], a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[flight attendant]] who was an early AIDS patient\n* [[Donal Logue]] as [[Bobbi Campbell]], an AIDS activist\n* [[B. D. Wong]] as Kico Govantes, a San Francisco artist and Bill Kraus' lover\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Luc Montagnier|Dr. Luc Montagnier]], a French virologist and one of the discoverers of HIV\n* [[Nathalie Baye]] as [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi|Dr. Fran\u00e7oise Barre]]\n* [[Phil Collins]] as Eddie Papasano, a San Francisco bathhouse owner<ref name=\"Not Dead Yet\">{{cite book|title=Not Dead Yet|author=[[Phil Collins]]|publisher=Century Books|location=[[London]], England|page=[https://archive.org/details/notdeadyetautobi0000coll/page/269 269]|isbn=978-1-780-89513-0|url=https://archive.org/details/notdeadyetautobi0000coll/page/269}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Martin]] as a Brother of an AIDS patient\n* [[Richard Gere]] as a choreographer who learns he has AIDS\n* [[David Marshall Grant]] as Dennis Seeley\n* [[Ronald Guttman]] as [[Jean-Claude Chermann|Dr. Jean-Claude Chermann]], a French virologist and manager of the research team that discovered HIV\n* [[Anjelica Huston]] as Dr. Betsy Reisz\n* [[Ken Jenkins]] as Dr. Dennis Donohue, an HIV researcher\n* [[Richard Jenkins]] as [[Marcus Conant|Dr. Marcus Conant]], a [[Dermatology|dermatologist]] and one of the first physicians to diagnose and treat AIDS\n* [[Tch\u00e9ky Karyo]] as [[Willy Rozenbaum|Dr. Willy Rozenbaum]], a French physician and one of the discoverers of HIV\n* [[Peter McRobbie]] as [[Max Essex|Dr. Max Essex]], one of the first to suspect that a [[retrovirus]] was the cause of AIDS and to determine that HIV could be transmitted through [[blood]]\n* [[Charles Martin Smith]] as Dr. Harold Jaffe, an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the CDC\n* [[Christian Clemenson]] as Dr. Dale Lawrence, a member of the CDC's Task Force on [[Kaposi's sarcoma]] and Opportunistic Infections\n* [[Rosemary Murphy]] as Blood Bank Executive\n* [[Stephen Spinella]] as Brandy Alexander\n* [[David Clennon]] as Mr. Johnstone\n* [[Swoosie Kurtz]] as Mrs. Johnstone, an AIDS patient\n* [[Lawrence Monoson]] as Chip\n* [[David Dukes]] as Dr. [[Mervyn Silverman]], San Francisco Director of Health\n}}\n\n==Closing montage==\nThe film closes with footage of a candlelight vigil and march in San Francisco, followed by a montage of images of numerous celebrities who have died of AIDS or were involved with HIV/AIDS education and research, accompanied by [[Elton John]] singing his \"[[The Last Song (Elton John song)|The Last Song]].\" The montage includes:\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Bobbi Campbell]]\n* [[Ryan White]]\n* [[Rock Hudson]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]]\n* [[Tina Chow]]\n* [[Rudolf Nureyev]]\n* [[Arthur Ashe]]\n* [[Michael Bennett (theater)|Michael Bennett]]\n* [[Liberace]]\n* [[Freddie Mercury]]\n* [[Elizabeth Glaser]]\n* [[Magic Johnson]]\n* [[Larry Kramer]]\n* [[Alison Gertz]]\n* [[Max Robinson]]\n* [[Halston]]\n* [[Willi Smith]]\n* [[Perry Ellis]]\n* [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]]\n* [[Steve Rubell]]\n* [[Keith Haring]]\n* [[Stewart McKinney (politician)|Stewart McKinney]]\n* [[Denholm Elliott]]\n* [[Brad Davis (actor)|Brad Davis]]\n* [[Amanda Blake]]\n* [[Robert Reed]]\n* [[Michel Foucault]]\n* [[Tom Waddell]]\n* [[Tested Positive Awareness (TPA) of Chicago photo from the book, \"Epitaphs for the Living: Words and Images in the Time of AIDS.  This photo  was taken on the Belmont Rocks...a gathering place for Gays and Lesbians in Chicago.  The photo includes Chris Clason and Jaye Goldberg]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Critical reception==\nMost reviewers agreed that the filmmakers had a daunting task in adapting Shilts's massive, fact-filled text into a dramatically coherent film. Many critics praised the results. Film review website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a [[List of films with a 100% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|100% \"Fresh\" rating]] based on eight reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/and_the_band_played_on/ |title=And the Band Played On (1993) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTony Scott of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated that \"if there are lapses, director Spottiswoode's engrossing, powerful work still accomplishes its mission: Shilts's book, with all its shock, sorrow and anger, has been transferred decisively to the screen.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Tony Scott |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117901186.html?categoryid=32&cs=1&p=0 |title=Review: ''And the Band Played On''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 30, 1993 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJohn O'Connor of ''[[The New York Times]]'' agreed that the adaptation \"adds up to tough and uncommonly courageous television. Excessive tinkering has left the pacing of the film sluggish in spots, but the story is never less than compelling.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=John J. O'Connor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/10/arts/tv-weekend-beyond-the-re-editing-rage-over-aids.html |title=TV Weekend; Beyond the Re-editing, Rage Over AIDS |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 10, 1993}}</ref>\n\n[[Ken Tucker]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' graded the film B+ and called it an \"intriguing, sometimes awkward, always earnest combination of docudrama, medical melodrama, and mystery story. The stars lend warmth to a movie necessarily preoccupied with cold research and politics, and they lend prestige: The movie must be important, since actors of this stature agreed to appear. The result of the stars' generosity, however, works against the movie by halting the flow of the drama every time a familiar face pops up on screen. The emotions and agony involved in this subject give ''Band'' an irresistible power, yet the movie's rhythm is choppy and the dialogue frequently stiff and clich\u00e9d. The best compliment one can pay this TV movie is to say that unlike so many fact-based films, it does not exploit or diminish the tragedy of its subject.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Ken Tucker]] |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,307958,00.html |title=And the Band Played On |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 10, 1993 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn a review from ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out New York]]'', the writing team thought \"so keen were the makers of this adaptation of Randy Shilts's best-seller to bombard us with the facts and figures of the history of AIDS that they forgot to offer a properly dramatic human framework to make us care fully about the characters.\" The review also says that the multiple issues the film attempts to cover \"make for a disjointed, clich\u00e9d narrative.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.timeout.com/film/newyork/reviews/77950/And_the_Band_Played_On.html |title=And the Band Played On |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out New York]] |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRichard Zoglin of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine wrote \"Shilts's prodigiously researched 600-page book has been boiled down to a fact-filled, dramatically coherent, occasionally moving 2 hours and 20 minutes. At a time when most made-for-TV movies have gone tabloid crazy, here is a rare one that tackles a big subject, raises the right issues, fights the good fight.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Zoglin |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,979190-1,00.html |title=Fighting The Good Fight |work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |date=September 13, 1993}}</ref>\n\nThe team from [[Channel 4]] believed the film \"is stifled by good intentions and a distractingly generous cast of stars in leads and cameos.\"\n\n==Accolades==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2018}}\n;[[Primetime Emmy Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/site-search?search_api_views_fulltext=And%20the%20Band%20Played%20On&f%5B0%5D=type%3Anominations|title=Television Academy - The People that bring you the Emmys|publisher=TELEVISION ACADEMY and ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Made for Television Movie]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Casting for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special|Outstanding Casting for a Miniseries or Special]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Editing for a Miniseries or Special \u2014 Single-Camera Production]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Matthew Modine]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Alan Alda]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Richard Gere]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Ian McKellen]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Swoosie Kurtz]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Lily Tomlin]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Directing for a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Roger Spottiswoode]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Writing in a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Makeup for a Limited Series or Movie (Non-Prosthetic)|Outstanding Makeup for a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Hairstyling for a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Hairstyling for a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* Outstanding Art Direction for a Miniseries or Special (nominated)\n\n;[[Golden Globe Award]]s\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Television Film]] (nominated)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]] ([[Matthew Modine]]) (nominated)\n\n;[[CableACE Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000140/1995/1/?ref_=ev_eh|title=CableACE Awards 1995|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* Best Movie or Miniseries (nominee)\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Ian McKellen]]) '''(won)'''\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Richard Gere]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Lawrence Monoson]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actress in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Swoosie Kurtz]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actress in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Lily Tomlin]]) (nominated)\n* Best Make-Up (nominee)\n\n;Misc.\n* [[Humanitas Prize]] (Arnold Schulman) '''(won)'''\n* [[GLAAD Media Award]] for Outstanding TV Movie '''(won)'''\n* [[Montreal World Film Festival]] Special Grand Prize of the Jury ([[Roger Spottiswoode]]) '''(won)'''\n* [[Casting Society of America|Casting Society of America Artios Award]] for Best Casting for TV Movie of the Week '''(won)'''\n* [[American Cinema Editors|American Cinema Editors Eddie Award]] for Best Edited Motion Picture for Non-Commercial Television '''(won)'''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n\n* [[1993 in television]]\n* ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'' (2014) \u2013 An [[HBO]] film also regarding the early years of the [[HIV/AIDS]] Crisis in the [[United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Amg movie}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''And the Band Played On''\n|list =\n{{EmmyAward TelevisionMovie}}\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding TV Movie or Limited Series}}\n}}\n{{Roger Spottiswoode}}\n{{Aaron Spelling}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:And The Band Played On (Film)}}\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:1993 television films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roger Spottiswoode]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Carter Burwell]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in film]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in television]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Made for Television Movie winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = And the Band Played On\n| image                = And The Band Played On Film Poster.jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Promotional poster\n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[And the Band Played On|And the Band Played On: Politics, People, and the AIDS Epidemic]]''|[[Randy Shilts]]}}\n| screenplay           = [[Arnold Schulman]]\n| director             = [[Roger Spottiswoode]]\n| starring             = {{unbulleted list|[[Matthew Modine]]|[[Alan Alda]]|[[Ian McKellen]]|[[Lily Tomlin]]|[[Richard Gere]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Carter Burwell]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = {{unbulleted list|Sarah Pillsbury|Midge Sanford}}\n| editor               = Lois Freeman-Fox\n| cinematography       = [[Paul Elliott (cinematographer)|Paul Elliott]]\n| runtime              = 141 minutes\n| company              = [[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = [[HBO]]\n| network              = HBO<br />[[NBC]]\n| budget               = $8 million\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1993|9|11}} \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''And the Band Played On''''' is a 1993 American [[television film]] [[docudrama]] directed by [[Roger Spottiswoode]]. The [[screenplay|teleplay]] by [[Arnold Schulman]] is based on the best-selling 1987 non-fiction book ''[[And the Band Played On|And the Band Played On: Politics, People, and the AIDS Epidemic]]'' by [[Randy Shilts]].\n\nThe film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]] before being broadcast by [[HBO]] on September 11, 1993. It later was released in the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Spain]], [[Germany]], [[Argentina]], [[Austria]], [[Italy]], [[Sweden]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Denmark]], [[New Zealand]], and [[Australia]]. The HBO movie was later aired on [[NBC]] in 1994. NBC (as well as [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]) were some of the networks considered to make a miniseries based on the book in the late 1980s, but the networks turned it down because they could not find a way to structure it as a two-night, four-hour miniseries. In 1994, NBC finally aired the movie with a parental discretion warning due to its sensitive subject matter.\n\n==Plot==\nIn a prologue set in 1976, American [[epidemiology|epidemiologist]] [[Don Francis]] arrives in a village on the banks of the [[Ebola River]] in [[Zaire]] and discovers many of the residents and the doctor working with them have died from a mysterious illness later identified as [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola hemorrhagic fever]]. It is his first exposure to such an [[epidemic]], and the images of the dead he helps [[cremation|cremate]] will haunt him when he later becomes involved with [[HIV/AIDS]] research at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].\n\nIn 1981, Francis becomes aware of a growing number of deaths from unexplained sources among [[gay]] men in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]] and [[San Francisco]], and is prompted to begin an in-depth investigation of the possible causes. Working with no money, limited space, and outdated equipment, he comes in contact with politicians, numerous members of the medical community (many of whom resent his involvement because of their personal agendas), and gay activists. Of the latter, some such as [[Bill Kraus]] support him, while others express resentment at what they see as unwanted interference in their lifestyles, especially in his attempts to close the local [[Gay bathhouse|bathhouses]]. One day, when exercising at a local gym, Kraus notices a spot at the base of his leg, worrying that it might be [[Kaposi's sarcoma]]. After a series of blood tests, Kraus is horrified that his worst fears have been confirmed when he learns that he has been diagnosed with AIDS. While Francis pursues his theory that AIDS is caused by a [[sexually transmitted infection|sexually transmitted virus]] on the model of [[feline leukemia virus|feline leukemia]], he finds his efforts are stonewalled by the CDC, which is unwilling to prove the disease is transmitted through blood, and competing [[France|French]] and [[United States|American]] scientists, particularly [[Robert Gallo|Dr. Robert Gallo]]. These medical researchers squabble about who should receive credit for discovering the virus. Meanwhile, the death toll climbs rapidly.\n\n==Principal cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Matthew Modine]] as [[Don Francis|Dr. Don Francis]], an epidemiologist, [[HIV/AIDS]] researcher, and one of the first scientists to suggest that AIDS was caused by an [[Pathogen|infectious agent]]\n* [[Alan Alda]] as [[Robert Gallo|Dr. Robert Gallo]], a biomedical researcher and one of the discoverers of HIV as the infectious agent responsible for [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]]\n* [[Ian McKellen]] as [[Bill Kraus]], a [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]] and AIDS activist and congressional aide\n* [[Glenne Headly]] as [[Mary Guinan|Dr. Mary Guinan]], an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]\n* [[Richard Masur]] as [[William Darrow|Dr. William Darrow]], one of the discoverers of HIV as the virus that causes AIDS\n* [[Saul Rubinek]] as Dr. James Curran, an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the CDC\n* [[Lily Tomlin]] as [[Selma Dritz|Dr. Selma Dritz]], a physician and epidemiologist\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]] as [[Ga\u00ebtan Dugas]], a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[flight attendant]] who was an early AIDS patient\n* [[Donal Logue]] as [[Bobbi Campbell]], an AIDS activist\n* [[B. D. Wong]] as Kico Govantes, a San Francisco artist and Bill Kraus' lover\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Luc Montagnier|Dr. Luc Montagnier]], a French virologist and one of the discoverers of HIV\n* [[Nathalie Baye]] as [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi|Dr. Fran\u00e7oise Barre]]\n* [[Phil Collins]] as Eddie Papasano, a San Francisco bathhouse owner<ref name=\"Not Dead Yet\">{{cite book|title=Not Dead Yet|author=[[Phil Collins]]|publisher=Century Books|location=[[London]], England|page=[https://archive.org/details/notdeadyetautobi0000coll/page/269 269]|isbn=978-1-780-89513-0|url=https://archive.org/details/notdeadyetautobi0000coll/page/269}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Martin]] as a Brother of an AIDS patient\n* [[Richard Gere]] as a choreographer who learns he has AIDS\n* [[David Marshall Grant]] as Dennis Seeley\n* [[Ronald Guttman]] as [[Jean-Claude Chermann|Dr. Jean-Claude Chermann]], a French virologist and manager of the research team that discovered HIV\n* [[Anjelica Huston]] as Dr. Betsy Reisz\n* [[Ken Jenkins]] as Dr. Dennis Donohue, an HIV researcher\n* [[Richard Jenkins]] as [[Marcus Conant|Dr. Marcus Conant]], a [[Dermatology|dermatologist]] and one of the first physicians to diagnose and treat AIDS\n* [[Tch\u00e9ky Karyo]] as [[Willy Rozenbaum|Dr. Willy Rozenbaum]], a French physician and one of the discoverers of HIV\n* [[Peter McRobbie]] as [[Max Essex|Dr. Max Essex]], one of the first to suspect that a [[retrovirus]] was the cause of AIDS and to determine that HIV could be transmitted through [[blood]]\n* [[Charles Martin Smith]] as Dr. Harold Jaffe, an investigator of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for the CDC\n* [[Christian Clemenson]] as Dr. Dale Lawrence, a member of the CDC's Task Force on [[Kaposi's sarcoma]] and Opportunistic Infections\n* [[Rosemary Murphy]] as Blood Bank Executive\n* [[Stephen Spinella]] as Brandy Alexander\n* [[David Clennon]] as Mr. Johnstone\n* [[Swoosie Kurtz]] as Mrs. Johnstone, an AIDS patient\n* [[Lawrence Monoson]] as Chip\n* [[David Dukes]] as Dr. [[Mervyn Silverman]], San Francisco Director of Health\n}}\n\n==Closing montage==\nThe film closes with footage of a candlelight vigil and march in San Francisco, followed by a montage of images of numerous celebrities who have died of AIDS or were involved with HIV/AIDS education and research, accompanied by [[Elton John]] singing his \"[[The Last Song (Elton John song)|The Last Song]].\" The montage includes:\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Bobbi Campbell]]\n* [[Ryan White]]\n* [[Rock Hudson]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]]\n* [[Tina Chow]]\n* [[Rudolf Nureyev]]\n* [[Arthur Ashe]]\n* [[Michael Bennett (theater)|Michael Bennett]]\n* [[Liberace]]\n* [[Freddie Mercury]]\n* [[Elizabeth Glaser]]\n* [[Magic Johnson]]\n* [[Larry Kramer]]\n* [[Alison Gertz]]\n* [[Max Robinson]]\n* [[Halston]]\n* [[Willi Smith]]\n* [[Perry Ellis]]\n* [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]]\n* [[Steve Rubell]]\n* [[Keith Haring]]\n* [[Stewart McKinney (politician)|Stewart McKinney]]\n* [[Denholm Elliott]]\n* [[Brad Davis (actor)|Brad Davis]]\n* [[Amanda Blake]]\n* [[Robert Reed]]\n* [[Michel Foucault]]\n* [[Tom Waddell]]\n* [[Tested Positive Awareness Organization of Chicago...including Chris Clason and Jaye Goldberg]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Critical reception==\nMost reviewers agreed that the filmmakers had a daunting task in adapting Shilts's massive, fact-filled text into a dramatically coherent film. Many critics praised the results. Film review website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a [[List of films with a 100% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|100% \"Fresh\" rating]] based on eight reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/and_the_band_played_on/ |title=And the Band Played On (1993) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTony Scott of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated that \"if there are lapses, director Spottiswoode's engrossing, powerful work still accomplishes its mission: Shilts's book, with all its shock, sorrow and anger, has been transferred decisively to the screen.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Tony Scott |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117901186.html?categoryid=32&cs=1&p=0 |title=Review: ''And the Band Played On''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 30, 1993 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJohn O'Connor of ''[[The New York Times]]'' agreed that the adaptation \"adds up to tough and uncommonly courageous television. Excessive tinkering has left the pacing of the film sluggish in spots, but the story is never less than compelling.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=John J. O'Connor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/10/arts/tv-weekend-beyond-the-re-editing-rage-over-aids.html |title=TV Weekend; Beyond the Re-editing, Rage Over AIDS |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 10, 1993}}</ref>\n\n[[Ken Tucker]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' graded the film B+ and called it an \"intriguing, sometimes awkward, always earnest combination of docudrama, medical melodrama, and mystery story. The stars lend warmth to a movie necessarily preoccupied with cold research and politics, and they lend prestige: The movie must be important, since actors of this stature agreed to appear. The result of the stars' generosity, however, works against the movie by halting the flow of the drama every time a familiar face pops up on screen. The emotions and agony involved in this subject give ''Band'' an irresistible power, yet the movie's rhythm is choppy and the dialogue frequently stiff and clich\u00e9d. The best compliment one can pay this TV movie is to say that unlike so many fact-based films, it does not exploit or diminish the tragedy of its subject.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Ken Tucker]] |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,307958,00.html |title=And the Band Played On |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 10, 1993 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn a review from ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out New York]]'', the writing team thought \"so keen were the makers of this adaptation of Randy Shilts's best-seller to bombard us with the facts and figures of the history of AIDS that they forgot to offer a properly dramatic human framework to make us care fully about the characters.\" The review also says that the multiple issues the film attempts to cover \"make for a disjointed, clich\u00e9d narrative.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.timeout.com/film/newyork/reviews/77950/And_the_Band_Played_On.html |title=And the Band Played On |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out New York]] |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRichard Zoglin of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine wrote \"Shilts's prodigiously researched 600-page book has been boiled down to a fact-filled, dramatically coherent, occasionally moving 2 hours and 20 minutes. At a time when most made-for-TV movies have gone tabloid crazy, here is a rare one that tackles a big subject, raises the right issues, fights the good fight.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Zoglin |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,979190-1,00.html |title=Fighting The Good Fight |work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |date=September 13, 1993}}</ref>\n\nThe team from [[Channel 4]] believed the film \"is stifled by good intentions and a distractingly generous cast of stars in leads and cameos.\"\n\n==Accolades==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2018}}\n;[[Primetime Emmy Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/site-search?search_api_views_fulltext=And%20the%20Band%20Played%20On&f%5B0%5D=type%3Anominations|title=Television Academy - The People that bring you the Emmys|publisher=TELEVISION ACADEMY and ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Made for Television Movie]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Casting for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special|Outstanding Casting for a Miniseries or Special]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Editing for a Miniseries or Special \u2014 Single-Camera Production]] '''(won)'''\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Matthew Modine]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Alan Alda]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Richard Gere]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Ian McKellen]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Swoosie Kurtz]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Lily Tomlin]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Directing for a Miniseries or Special]] ([[Roger Spottiswoode]]) (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Writing in a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Makeup for a Limited Series or Movie (Non-Prosthetic)|Outstanding Makeup for a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Hairstyling for a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Hairstyling for a Miniseries or Special]] (nominated)\n* Outstanding Art Direction for a Miniseries or Special (nominated)\n\n;[[Golden Globe Award]]s\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Television Film]] (nominated)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]] ([[Matthew Modine]]) (nominated)\n\n;[[CableACE Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000140/1995/1/?ref_=ev_eh|title=CableACE Awards 1995|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* Best Movie or Miniseries (nominee)\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Ian McKellen]]) '''(won)'''\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Richard Gere]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actor in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Lawrence Monoson]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actress in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Swoosie Kurtz]]) (nominated)\n* Best Supporting Actress in a Movie or Miniseries ([[Lily Tomlin]]) (nominated)\n* Best Make-Up (nominee)\n\n;Misc.\n* [[Humanitas Prize]] (Arnold Schulman) '''(won)'''\n* [[GLAAD Media Award]] for Outstanding TV Movie '''(won)'''\n* [[Montreal World Film Festival]] Special Grand Prize of the Jury ([[Roger Spottiswoode]]) '''(won)'''\n* [[Casting Society of America|Casting Society of America Artios Award]] for Best Casting for TV Movie of the Week '''(won)'''\n* [[American Cinema Editors|American Cinema Editors Eddie Award]] for Best Edited Motion Picture for Non-Commercial Television '''(won)'''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n\n* [[1993 in television]]\n* ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'' (2014) \u2013 An [[HBO]] film also regarding the early years of the [[HIV/AIDS]] Crisis in the [[United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Amg movie}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''And the Band Played On''\n|list =\n{{EmmyAward Te