phic Agency|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kolbe, Saint of Auschwitz\">{{cite web|url=http://auschwitz.dk/Kolbe.htm |title=Kolbe, Saint of Auschwitz |publisher=Auschwitz.dk |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Michael2008\">{{cite book|last=Michael |first=Robert |title=A History of Catholic Antisemitism: The Dark Side of the Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ZnFAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA154|date=1 April 2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-61117-7|page=154}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"National Shrine of St. Maximilian Kolbe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marytown.com/content/national-shrine-of-st-maximilian-kolbe|title=National Shrine of St. Maximilian Kolbe|accessdate=30 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006103829/http://www.marytown.com/content/national-shrine-of-st-maximilian-kolbe|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Niepokalan\u00f3w\">{{cite web|url=http://www.franciszkanie-warszawa.pl/niepokalanow|title=Niepokalan\u00f3w|accessdate=30 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006114330/http://www.franciszkanie-warszawa.pl/niepokalanow|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OFMI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofmi.net/friars.html |title=O.F.M.I. Friars |publisher=Franciscan Friars of Mary Immaculate |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"peterson\">{{cite book|last=Peterson |first=Anna L. |title=Martyrdom and the Politics of Religion: Progressive Catholicism in El Salvador's Civil War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieyeKxd8BfoC&pg=PA94|year=1997|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-3182-5|page=94}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Plunka2012\">{{cite book|last=Plunka |first=Gene A. |title=Staging Holocaust Resistance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RQPHAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA21|date=24 April 2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-00061-3|page=21}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"psb296\">Czes\u0142aw Lechicki, ''Kolbe Rajmund'', Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny, Tom XIII, 1968, p. 296</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"psb297\">Czes\u0142aw Lechicki, ''Kolbe Rajmund'', Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny, Tom XIII, 1968, p. 297</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Publishing2013\">{{cite book|author=Catholic Way Publishing|title=My Daily Prayers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jVfpAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT249|date=27 December 2013|publisher=Catholic Way Publishing|isbn=978-1-78379-029-6|page=249}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"qrz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.qrz.com/db/SP3RN |title=SP3RN @ |publisher=qrz.com |accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"relics\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastoralcentre.pl/first-class-relics-st-maximilian-kolbe/ |publisher=Pastoral Centre|title=The First-Class Relics of St Maximilian Kolbe|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sanktuarium \u015aw. Maksymiliana \u2013 Zdu\u0144ska Wola \u2013 DIECEZJA W\u0141OC\u0141AWSKA -KURIA DIECEZJALNA W\u0141OC\u0141AWSKA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diecezja.wloclawek.pl/pl/262/sanktuarium-sw-maksymiliana-zdunska-wola|title=Sanktuarium \u015aw. Maksymiliana \u2013 Zdu\u0144ska Wola \u2013 DIECEZJA W\u0141OC\u0141AWSKA -KURIA DIECEZJALNA W\u0141OC\u0141AWSKA|accessdate=30 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006074002/http://www.diecezja.wloclawek.pl/pl/262/sanktuarium-sw-maksymiliana-zdunska-wola|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"senat\">UCHWA\u0141A SENATU RZECZYPOSPOLITEJ POLSKIEJ z dnia 21 pa\u017adziernika 2010 r.o og\u0142oszeniu roku 2011 Rokiem \u015awi\u0119tego Maksymiliana Marii Kolbego [http://www.senat.gov.pl/k7/dok/uch/063/930uch.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806032336/http://www.senat.gov.pl/k7/dok/uch/063/930uch.pdf |date=6 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sixty-ninth Anniversary of the Death of St. Maximilian Kolbe\">{{cite web|url=http://en.auschwitz.org/m/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=795&Itemid=8 |title=Sixty-ninth Anniversary of the Death of St. Maximilian Kolbe |publisher=Auschwitz-Birkenau Memorial and Museum |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"smmkolbeci\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smmkolbe.pl|title=Parafia p.w.w. M.M. Kolbego w Szczecinie \u2013 Aktualno\u015bci|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Strzelecka1984\">{{cite book|last=Strzelecka |first=Kinga |title=Maksymilian M. Kolbe: f\u00fcr andere leben und sterben|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XBeCGwAACAAJ|year=1984|publisher=S&#91;ank&#93;t-Benno-Verlag|page=6|language=German}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"University of Dayton Marian prayers\">{{cite web |url=http://campus.udayton.edu/mary//prayers/consec01.html#2 |title=University of Dayton Marian prayers |publisher=Campus.udayton.edu |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=10 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211015531/http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/prayers/consec01.html#2 |archive-date=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"westminster\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/our-history/people/maximilian-kolbe |title=Maximilian Kolbe |publisher=Westminster Abbey |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Yallop2012\">{{cite book|last=Yallop |first=David |title=The Power & the Glory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Xs8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT203|date=23 August 2012|publisher=Constable & Robinson Limited|isbn=978-1-4721-0516-5|page=203}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Zizek2012\">{{cite book|last=Zizek |first=Slavoj |title=Less Than Nothing: Hegel and the Shadow of Dialectical Materialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FAqM5rxWWKwC&pg=PA121|date=22 May 2012|publisher=Verso Books|isbn=978-1-84467-902-7|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Rees\n|first=Laurence\n|year=2005\n|title=Auschwitz: A New History\n|url=https://archive.org/details/auschwitznewhist00rees\n|url-access=registration\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Public Affairs\n|isbn=978-1-58648-357-9\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080416201907/http://saints.sqpn.com/saintm01.htm Patron Saints Index: Saint Maximilian Kolbe<!-- bot-generated title -->]\n* [http://david-gooderson.co.uk/stage-plays/kolbes-gift.php ''Kolbe's Gift''], a play by David Gooderson about Kolbe and his self-sacrifice in Auschwitz based on factual evidence and conversations with the late [[J\u00f3zef Garli\u0144ski]]\n* [http://www.pastoralcentre.pl/st-maximilian-kolbe-kazimierz-braun/ A Man Feared by the 21st Century: Saint Maximilian Kolbe from the Starvation Bunker in Auschwitz] \u2013 a drama by [[:pl:Kazimierz Braun (re\u017cyser)|Kazimierz Braun]]\n* [http://catholicism.org/maximilian-kolbe.html ''Saint Maximilian Kolbe''], a popular biography at Catholicism.org\n* [http://niepokalanow.eu./ Niepokalan\u00f3w in English]\n* [http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=370 ''Catholic Online, St. Maximilian Kolbe''], Catholic Online.Inform-Inspire-Ignite.\n* [http://www.saintmaximiliankolbe.com/ St. Maximilian Kolbe Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GDccf5cAFCU An \"Insight\" episode which mentions Maximilian Kolbe, who was portrayed by [[Werner Klemperer]]]\n\n{{canonization}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|Poland|Saints|World War II}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolbe, Maximilian}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Zdu\u0144ska Wola]]\n[[Category:People from Kalisz Governorate]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic martyrs]]\n[[Category:Anglican saints]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:Canonizations by Pope John Paul II]]\n[[Category:Catholic saints and blesseds of the Nazi era]]\n[[Category:Conventual Friars Minor]]\n[[Category:Polish Franciscans]]\n[[Category:Executed German Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Martyred Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:People celebrated in the Lutheran liturgical calendar]]\n[[Category:Polish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Polish civilians killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Polish people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people who died in Auschwitz concentration camp]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholic saints]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pontifical University of St. Bonaventure alumni]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n[[Category:Amateur radio people]]\n", "name_user": "98.168.224.89", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eChildhood)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximilian_Kolbe"}
{"title_page": "Criticism of NASCAR", "text_new": "{{short description|Negative depictions of NASCAR}}\nThe '''National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing (NASCAR)''' is the sanctioning body for the [[NASCAR Cup Series]], the [[Xfinity Series]] and the [[Gander RV & Outdoors Truck Series]].  [[NASCAR]] also administers a number of [[NASCAR Home Tracks|regional racing series]], including the [[Whelen Modified Tour]], and the [[Whelen All-American Series]], as well as international series in [[NASCAR Pinty's Series|Canada]], [[NASCAR Mexico Series|Mexico]], and [[NASCAR Whelen Euro Series|Europe]].\n\nSimilar to other professional motor racing leagues and sanctioning bodies, NASCAR has been a target of criticism on a variety of issues.  Some critics note the significant differences between present day NASCAR vehicles and true \"[[stock car]]s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.nascar.com/madcowracing/blog/2010/03/03/the_real_reason_nascar_is_less_stock|title=News & Media|accessdate=30 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008133306/http://community.nascar.com/madcowracing/blog/2010/03/03/the_real_reason_nascar_is_less_stock|archive-date=8 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Another topic of debate has been NASCAR's move to larger markets; in 1997, NASCAR added the [[Auto Club Speedway|California]] and [[Texas Motor Speedway]], respectively located in the metro areas of [[Los Angeles]] and [[Dallas]].  This caused NASCAR to move away from traditional tracks such as [[Rockingham Speedway|Rockingham]], which has led to some fans feeling that NASCAR abandoned its core market.<ref>{{cite web |last1=D'Eletto |first1=James |title=NASCAR: North Wilkesboro and Other Forgotten Tracks of the Sport |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1046666-nascar-north-wilkesboro-and-other-forgotten-tracks-of-the-sport |website=Bleacher Report |publisher=WarnerMedia |accessdate=29 March 2019 |language=English |date=1 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carlton |first1=Chuck |title=Is NASCAR losing traditional fan base? |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/635200575/Is-NASCAR-losing-traditional-fan-base.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Deseret News (via The Dallas Morning News) |publisher=Deseret News Publishing |date=16 April 2006 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|igP1Q-KMO6U&t=|\"The Rise and Fall of NASCAR\"}}</ref>\n\nOthers cite the dominance of the [[France family]] (and [[Brian France]] in particular) in NASCAR's business structure, policies, and decision making.  Recently, the increased number of Cup drivers competing consistently in the [[Xfinity Series]] races has been hotly debated. NASCAR has been challenged on the types and frequency of [[Caution flag#Yellow flag|caution flags]], with some critics suggesting the outcome of races is being manipulated,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autoracingsport.com/skinner-joins-stewart-in-exposing-nascar-manipulation/ |title=Skinner joins Stewart in exposing NASCAR manipulation |publisher=Autoracingsport.com |accessdate=2012-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224232432/http://autoracingsport.com/skinner-joins-stewart-in-exposing-nascar-manipulation/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/377065-jimmie-johnson-and-jeff-gordon-did-nascar-manipulate-phoenix-results|title=Jimmie Johnson and Jeff Gordon: Did NASCAR Manipulate Phoenix Results?|first=David|last=Yeazell|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://autoracingsport.com/we-want-your-vote-does-nascar-manipulate-its-races-in-any-way/ |title=Does NASCAR manipulate its races in any way? |publisher=Autoracingsport.com |accessdate=2012-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224232437/http://autoracingsport.com/we-want-your-vote-does-nascar-manipulate-its-races-in-any-way/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref> and that the intention is not safety, as NASCAR claims, but closer racing.\n\nSince its peak in 2005, NASCAR has seen a gradual decline, with its TV viewership reaching record lows in 2018<ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR 2018 TV Ratings |url=http://www.espn.com/jayski/pages/story/_/id/22408275/nascar-2018-tv-ratings |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=28 November 2018}}</ref> and race day attendance suffering to record lows as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pockrass |first1=Bob |title=NASCAR teams get creative with sponsors following dip in ratings, attendance |url=http://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/24263283/nascar-checking-speedway-motorsports-inc-earnings-attendance-ratings-first-half-2018-season |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=2 August 2018}}</ref> Reasons cited for its decline include the aforementioned track changes, the introduction of the [[Car of Tomorrow]] which both drivers and fans alike criticized,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Car Of Tomorrow Fuzzy Math And Fuzzier Logic|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/MD80891/84436|magazine=[[Sporting News]]|accessdate=15 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212090228/http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/MD80891/84436|archivedate=2009-02-12|date=May 18, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |title=Postrace comments on 2008 Best Buy 400 |access-date=2019-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312102706/http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |archive-date=2016-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015>{{cite web|last1=Turner|first1=Jared|title=Brian France reveals his biggest failure as NASCAR chairman|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nascar/story/brian-france-nascar-chairman-biggest-failure-car-of-tomorrow-032015|website=[[Fox Sports]]|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|accessdate=22 March 2015|date=March 20, 2015}}</ref> the constant tinkering of the rules of its championship and the racing itself,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jacobs |first1=Christopher |title=NASCAR Is Ruining Stock Car Racing, One Rule Change At a Time |url=https://thefederalist.com/2017/02/24/nascar-ruining-stock-car-racing-one-rule-change-time/ |website=The Federalist |publisher=FDRLST Media |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=24 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Caldwell |first1=Dave |title=NASCAR Fans Are Racing Away From The Sport Even Faster |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davecaldwell/2018/05/02/stock-car-fans-continue-racing-away-from-nascar/#64bb5b3a1df5 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes Media, LLC |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=2 May 2018}}</ref> the change in its race day experience,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gluck |first1=Jeff |title=Fans explain why they stopped attending NASCAR races |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2016/07/01/nascar-fans-attendance-cost/86587042/ |website=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> the perceived decline in the quality of its racing,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fryer |first1=Jenna |title=NASCAR tries to end slide with push for more exciting racing |url=https://wlos.com/sports/content/nascar-tries-to-end-slide-with-push-for-more-exciting-racing |accessdate=29 March 2019 |publisher=ABC 13 WLOS}}</ref> and the retirement of its past stars.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruce |first1=Kenny |title=How a retiring star exposed NASCAR's |url=https://www.autosport.com/nascar/feature/8245/how-a-retiring-star-exposed-nascar-big-problem |website=Autosport |publisher=Motorsport Network |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR needs new stars and Kyle Larson may save the sport |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2019/02/01/nascar-needs-new-stars-and-kyle-larson-may-save-the-sport/38989823/ |website=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnother general area of criticism, not only of NASCAR, but other [[motorsport]]s as well, includes questions about [[Gasoline|fuel]] consumption,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mndaily.com/2008/06/04/nascar-waste-resources |title=NASCAR a waste of resources |publisher=Mndaily.com |date=2008-06-04 |accessdate=2012-08-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319224928/http://www.mndaily.com/2008/06/04/nascar-waste-resources |archive-date=2012-03-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Exhaust gas|emission]]s, [[engine]] [[decibels|noise levels]], and [[air pollutants|pollution]], and the use of [[Tetraethyllead|lead additives]] in the [[gasoline]].\n\n==The [[Car of Tomorrow]] and changes in stock car style==\n[[Image:KennyWallace2006Car.jpg|thumb|[[Mark McFarland]] (88) spins at [[Bristol Motor Speedway]], while [[Kenny Wallace]] (22) and [[Ashton Lewis Jr.]] (25) pass to the inside during a [[Busch Series]] event in 2006, using Gen-4 cars.]]\n[[File:Dodge Charger NASCAR (Montreal).jpg|thumb|left|The Car of Tomorrow model on display in January 2008. Drivers and fans alike criticized the aesthetics of the car, and some have cited the Car of Tomorrow for contributing to the decline of NASCAR.]]\nBeginning in the early 2000s, NASCAR researched and worked on a new model to introduce towards the end of the decade. One particular area of scrutiny was driver safety; [[Dale Earnhardt]] [[Death of Dale Earnhardt|fatally crashed]] at the [[2001 Daytona 500]], and the safety of the cars used at the time was questioned.\n\nThe Car of Tomorrow was first tested in December 2005, and was first revealed to the public in 2006, with numerous safety improvements being touted. The Car of Tomorrow made its debut at the [[2007 Food City 500]], and was almost immediately criticized by both fans and drivers alike. Many fans disliked the large and boxy design, its more generic appearance and the use of a detached wing.<ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015/> [[Kyle Busch]], who won the first race using the model, proclaimed that the car \"sucks\" after his victory and expanded on this criticism at Dover in 2008 by noting how the CoT was \"hitting a wall of air\" in the wake of a leading car, thus neutralizing ability to close up on leaders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |title=Postrace comments on 2008 Best Buy 400 |access-date=2019-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312102706/http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |archive-date=2016-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Busch was not the only driver to vent his frustrations; [[Jeff Gordon]] was also critical of the car, stating after the [[2007 Lenox Industrial Tools 300|2007 New England 300]], \"I'd like to know who it was who said this car would reduce the [[aerodynamics|aero]] [[understeer|push]] because I could have told you from when I first drove this car that it would be worse.\"<ref>[http://monkeesfan.blogspot.com/2007/07/plenty-of-subplots-at-hew-hampshire.html Plenty Of Subplots At New Hampshire]</ref>\n\nDespite the criticism, NASCAR fully implemented the model in [[2008 in NASCAR|2008]], and overall brought dramatic safety improvements and reduced costs of car maintenance.<ref name=ESPN-CoT-Thanks-for-the-memories>{{cite web|last1=McGee|first1=Ryan|title=Thanks for the memories, CoT|url=http://espn.go.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/8950107/nascar-car-tomorrow-buried-praised|website=[[ESPN|espn.go.com]]|publisher=[[ESPN]], [[ESPN The Magazine]]|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=February 15, 2013}}</ref> Despite the overall safety improvements, one point of contention was that the rear wing increased the severity of on-track accidents by causing cars to be more prone to flipping over or going airborne at higher speeds. After 3 such incidents between 2007 and 2010, NASCAR switched to a more traditional rear spoiler instead.<ref name=ESPN-CoT-Thanks-for-the-memories/>\n\nIn a retrospective interview in 2015, Brian France believed that the introduction of the model as his biggest failure, due to the lack of manufacturer identity, as well as its perceived effects on its racing.<ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015 /><ref name=Freep-BrianFranceCoT-2015>{{cite news|last1=Brudenell|first1=Mike|title=NASCAR top executive in Detroit: We'll 'make mistakes': NASCAR CEO and chairman Brian France speaks at Detroit Economic Club in Dearborn today to high schoolers and college students.|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/motor/2015/03/19/nascar-brian-france-detroit-economic-club/25044179/|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|accessdate=15 August 2015|date=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Even after the implementation of the [[Generation 6 (NASCAR)|Generation 6]] model, some fans still cite the Car of Tomorrow for causing the decline of NASCAR. Writer Christopher Smith of Car Throttle wrote that, \"...Nascar rules pretty much require all the race cars to be the same - no individuality aside from stickers that differentiate the models. Nascar television ratings and fan interest has been decreasing for years, and as far as I\u2019m concerned, this is the main reason.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Christopher |title=The Cars That Ruined Nascar, And How There's Hope For The Future |url=https://www.carthrottle.com/post/the-cars-that-ruined-nascar-and-how-theres-hope-for-the-future/ |website=Car Throttle |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Gen-6 cars themselves, while somewhat better received than the Car of Tomorrow (Generation 5) cars were at the time, have received some blow-back. [[Denny Hamlin]] was most critical, saying, \"I don't want to be the pessimist, but it did not race as good as our generation 5 or regular [[Car of Tomorrow|CoT]] cars did.\" Hamlin received a $25,000 fine for his comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar-news/4483224-denny-hamlin-fine-critical-comments-sprint-cup-car-gen-6-racing-phoenix|title=Denny Hamlin fined $25,000 for criticizing new Sprint Cup car, racing at Phoenix|date=March 7, 2013|author=Pockrass, Bob|work=Sporting News|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Engine noise levels==\nIn 2007, a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article cited two studies conducted by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]], conducted during races at [[Bristol Motor Speedway]] in 2005, which found that engine noise levels can reach as high as 140 [[decibels]], which can do severe damage to a person's sense of hearing. One NIOSH engineer stated that 43 cars during a race was \"equivalent to a jet engine\". The first study focused exclusively on Bristol Motor Speedway, while the second study took other NASCAR race tracks into account, and both studies found that noise levels regularly exceeded 140 decibels when the race cars were accelerating at full throttle, and that the noise levels lasted, on average, about three to four hours, the average duration of a NASCAR race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/26/sports/othersports/26noise.html|title=The Sound and the Fury, and Possibly the Danger|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 26, 2007}}</ref> The article cites 7-time NASCAR Cup Series champion [[Richard Petty]], as well as other drivers such as [[Jeff Burton]], now requiring the use of [[hearing aids]] due to hearing loss caused by engine noise. According to the article, a NIOSH engineer suggested putting mufflers on the cars in order to reduce the noise, but a NASCAR spokesperson stated that they already tried that in the 1960s, and it did not work as intended.\n\n==Business structure and decision-making policies==\nSince its founding in 1947 by [[William France Sr.]], the overall NASCAR organization has been majority owned by the France family, ensuring that the family controls a majority of the revenue that the sport generates. NASCAR is also criticized for its reluctance to promote some aspects of safety that it would have to pay for (''e.g.'', traveling safety crew),<ref>[http://cbs.sportsline.com/b/page/pressbox/0,1328,3544996,00.html CBS Sportsline.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017013734/http://cbs.sportsline.com/b/page/pressbox/0%2C1328%2C3544996%2C00.html |date=October 17, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/mld/kansascity/sports/motorsports/14558242.htm|title=KC Breaking News, Sports, Weather & More - KansasCity.com & The Kansas City Star|website=www.kansascity.com|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> and other allegedly monopolistic aspects such as merchandising and race-track ownership.\n\nIn addition, due to its influence and lack of drivers' say, NASCAR has been described as a \"benevolent dictatorship,\" with a top-heavy command structure that tends to keep dissenters in line.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Keefe |first=Brian |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/09/05/8271412/index.htm |title=CNN Money Magazine (online) |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2005-09-05 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/nascar/2005-06-20-nascar-debacle_x.htm USA Today], June 20, 2005</ref> Examples of such influence included the cancellation of the [[Speed Channel]] television show ''[[Pit Bull (TV series)|Pit Bull]]'' (which frequently criticized many of NASCAR's decisions and policies and enjoyed modest ratings), frequent use of the vague \"detrimental to NASCAR\" rule, and the creation of rules on whim, especially during a race. NASCAR has taken to penalizing drivers in recent years, with fines, point penalties, and lap penalties in races for drivers or mechanics who use obscene language in interviews to the media.<ref>[http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/05/092305Poe.asp SpeedWayMedia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213033559/http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/05/092305Poe.asp |date=December 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBecause of Fox Sports' heavy affiliation with NASCAR, a fair amount of the network's programming is NASCAR-related.\n\n==Driver competition in multiple series==\n[[File:KyleBuschToyotaMilwaukeeMile2009.jpg|thumb|right|2009 Nationwide Series car of Cup Series regular [[Kyle Busch]], who won the Nationwide Series championship that year]]\nNASCAR has long allowed drivers to compete in as many series and events as they like, with few restrictions. However, in recent years, many Cup Series drivers have competed in and dominated the lower tier Xfinity Series races on a regular basis, earning Cup drivers the nickname \"[[Buschwhacker]]s\" (derived from the 1984\u20132007 sponsorship of NASCAR's second-highest series by [[Busch Beer]]). The situation is compounded by the close timing of the races in the two series: a typical NASCAR weekend has a Xfinity race on Saturday followed by a Cup race on Sunday at the same track. Some have wondered why \"major league\" Cup drivers are allowed to compete in the \"minor league\" races with such frequency, and whether Xfinity is an adequate developmental series. Sportswriter Bob Margolis noted that much of this is due to the similarities between the cars used in the two series (they are mostly alike except for the engines and the wheelbase), and the desire for Cup drivers to get as much practice time as possible to learn about the track and car setup before the main race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=bm-buschpreview021706&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=Sports.Yahoo.com |publisher=Sports.Yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nIn the aforementioned 2008 meetings between NASCAR and Detroit automakers, the automakers also called for the Xfinity Series to become strictly a developmental series, with Cup drivers prohibited from running in the junior series.<ref name=Autoextremist>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoextremist.com/fumes1/2008/8/4/fumes-457.html |title=Fumes #457 \u2013 The Detroit Three get down to the business of NASCAR |first=Peter M. |last=De Lorenzo |publisher=Autoextremist.com |date=2008-08-06 |accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref>  The request was rejected at that time. However, in late 2010, media reports began to indicate that NASCAR may institute a slightly modified version of this rule for 2011, with Cup drivers allowed to run in Xfinity races but not to compete for the series championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/nascar/cup/columns/story?columnist=blount_terry&id=5842177 |title=The best and worst of 2010 |first=Terry |last=Blount |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 23, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> In January 2011, ''NASCAR.com'' confirmed this, adding that drivers will now be allowed to compete for the championship in only one national series in a given season, a change that also affects the [[Camping World Truck Series|Truck Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news/110110/rule-change-drivers-one-championship/index.html |title=NASCAR drivers must elect championships in '11 |first=Dave |last=Rodman |publisher=NASCAR.com |date=January 11, 2011 |accessdate=January 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlthough many claim that the added track time gained by running a Xfinity or Truck Series race helps drivers during the Cup Series race, any positive effects are not seen in final championship standings. For example, during his run of 5 consecutive Cup Series Championships, [[Jimmie Johnson]] ran only 3 Busch/Nationwide races in 2006, 1 each in 2007 and 2008, and none in 2009 or 2010. Another example is the 2009 season, where [[Kyle Busch]] won the [[2009 NASCAR Nationwide Series|Nationwide Series]] championship but failed to qualify for the 2009 [[NASCAR Chase for the Championship|Cup Series Chase]].\n\nOn October 2016, NASCAR announced new participation guidelines for its three national series, limiting the amount of Xfinity Series and Truck Series races that full-time drivers in its premier series will be allowed to compete in, starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/en_us/news-media/articles/2016/10/26/2017-limitations-sprint-cup-drivers-xfinity-truck-series-races.html |title=New participation guidelines put limits in place for 2017 |first=Zack |last=Albert |publisher=NASCAR.com |date=October 26, 2016 |accessdate=October 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental effects==\n\n===Fuel consumption===\n[[File:SunocoDispenserRoadAmerica2010Bucyros200.jpg|thumb|right|NASCAR fuel supply truck in 2010]]\nAccording to NASCAR, about 6,000 U.S. gallons (~23 kilolitres) of fuel are consumed during a typical Cup Series weekend.<ref name = \"Finney\">{{cite web | first = Mike | last = Finney | title = Like the cars, fuel goes fast in NASCAR | publisher = The (Wilmington, Del.) News Journal | date = January 2, 2006 | url = http://www.azcentral.com/sports/speed/articles/0602nascargas-ON.html | work = AZCentral.com | accessdate = 2007-11-19}}</ref> For the 2006 season, which included 36 points races, the total for the season would have been 216,000 U.S. gallons (818 kilolitres).\nOne environmental critic recently estimated NASCAR's total fuel consumption across all series at 2 million U.S. gallons (7,570 kilolitres) of gas for one season.<ref name = \"E\">{{cite web | first = Jean | last = Gerard | title = Motor Madness: Gas Guzzling is Business as Usual at NASCAR | publisher = E/The Environmental Magazine | url = http://www.emagazine.com/view/?2947&printview | accessdate = 2007-11-18 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927213046/http://www.emagazine.com/view/?2947&printview | archive-date = 2007-09-27 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nAt race speeds, Cup Series cars get 2 to 5 miles per gallon.<ref name = \"Finney\" /><ref name = \"E\" /><ref>{{cite web|first=Natale |last=Servino |title=NASCAR goes green? New tracks touted as good for the planet |publisher=Earth Island Journal |url=http://www.earthisland.org/EIJOURNAL/new_articles.cfm?articleID=981&journalID=84 |accessdate=2007-11-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013133428/http://earthisland.org/EIJOURNAL/new_articles.cfm?articleID=981&journalID=84 |archivedate=2007-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Consumption under caution can be estimated at 14-18 mpg, based on comparable engines generally available to the public. The ''rate'' of fuel consumption tends to be the same regardless of the actual speeds of the cars, as teams change gear ratios for each race to ensure that the engine always operates in its optimum power band; however, the fuel ''mileage'' will vary for each race, depending on the maximum speeds attained.\n\nThe fuel consumption criticism dates to 1974 and the [[1973 oil crisis|energy crisis]]; NASCAR responded by showing data that racing was far less consumptive of fuel than regular air travel, etc.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n===Emissions and pollution===\nThe consumption figures above provide no insight on environmental impact in terms of emissions. NASCAR vehicles are generally unregulated by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]], and in particular, they have no mufflers, catalytic converters or other emissions control devices. However, some local short tracks which run under NASCAR sanction require certain emissions control devices. Many short tracks run mufflers in compliance with noise ordinances at some tracks; in the early years of the [[Camping World Truck Series]], some races were held at venues which required mufflers, a requirement still used in NASCAR's K&N Pro Series (East and West) and Whelen (North and South) Modified Tours.\n\nNASCAR continued to use [[Unleaded gasoline#Lead|lead additives]] in its race gasoline until the [[2007 Auto Club 500]] at [[California Speedway]] on February 25,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scenedaily.com/stories/2006/10/16/scene_daily394.html |title=Nextel Cup going to unleaded fuel in 2007 |accessdate=2007-06-17 |author=Bob Passrock |date=October 21, 2006 |work=scenedaily.com}}</ref> which led to concerns about the health of those exposed to the fumes of the cars (fans and residents living near the race tracks). Lead is a well-known environmental risk, but the performance needs of race engines (in particular, the high [[Compression Ratio|compression ratios]] and sustained/repeated operation at high rpm and load) once made it difficult to switch to un[[Tetraethyllead|leaded fuel]].\n\nIn the United States, the commercial use of leaded fuel has been phased out since the early 1970s, when catalytic converters were required to be installed on new cars, making unleaded fuel a requirement (leaded fuel will destroy a [[catalytic converter]]). The sale of leaded fuel has been mostly banned in the US since 1996, but exemptions exist for auto racing, aircraft, farm and marine equipment.\n\nNASCAR eventually took steps to eliminate the need for leaded fuels. In 1998, NASCAR and then-fuel supplier [[Tosco Corporation|Tosco]] (Now [[ConocoPhillips]], the company that produces the [[Union 76]] brand of fuel) conducted an unsuccessful test of unleaded fuel in selected Busch Series races. In July 2006, in the first in a four-week test run of unleaded fuel, the first race since 1998 to run unleaded gasoline, known as [[Sunoco]] 260 GT Plus, a commercially available racing fuel, was held during a Busch race at the [[Gateway International Raceway]] in [[Madison, Illinois]]. The testing in July 2006 was successful with no suspected engine failures or malfunctions from the new fuel. In October 2006, NASCAR stated its intention to transition to unleaded fuel in all three top series (Craftsman, Busch and Cup) in 2007, starting with the [[Auto Club 500]].\n\nDuring the first race in which unleaded fuel was used, there were a number of engine failures during the race, leading many to believe that the unleaded fuel is to be blamed.  The drivers who encountered failures include [[Dale Earnhardt, Jr.]] and [[Martin Truex Jr.]] of [[Dale Earnhardt, Inc.]] and [[Kasey Kahne]] of [[Evernham Motorsports]]. The engine failures of both Earnhardt and Truex were attributed in part to the lack of a lead additive, but also to centrifugal force causing improper distribution of oil between the left and right sides of the engine. Evernham Motorsports has not disclosed the reason behind Kahne's engine failure.\n\nThe 2008 season marked the first season all 36 races used unleaded racing fuel.\n\n2011 marked one of the largest \u201cgreen initiatives\u201d in the fifty plus year history of NASCAR when all fuel sources were to include Ethanol in a blend called E15.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Rodman, NASCAR.COM |url=http://www.nascar.com/news/110122/ethanol-details-thunder/index.html |title=Fill 'er up: Teams off and running with E15 fuel - Jan 22, 2011 |publisher=Nascar.Com |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>  One unintended consequence of the conversion was higher horsepower and therefore slightly lower fuel economy.  It is argued however, that the reduction in fuel economy and the resultant increase in fuel use may offset any environmental impact savings by reduced emissions.  Although not connected to the fuel blend, a new \u201cDry Break\u201d self-venting fuel supply can was also adopted in part for safety (reduced the number of people working on the racecar during a pit stop) but also in part to reduce the amount of fuel spilled during a pit stop, which has both environmental and safety implications.  The reduced fuel spillage is negligible at best when observing a pit stop as fuel spills are common and during competition there is no real method to determine with any certainty the volume of fuel lost.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\nIn 2012 a complete technology change and shift in thinking occurred when NASCAR switched the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series to [[Fuel injection in NASCAR|fuel injection]] from the current carburetor. Arguments have been made about increased efficiency; however, race teams will work to ensure they take advantage of the additional horsepower and efficiency to increase speeds so any improvement in efficiency may be lost to competition.\n\n==Participation of non-American manufacturers==\n[[Image:Auto Show 067.jpg|thumb|left|A Gen-5 car body with [[Toyota Camry]] decals.]]\nNASCAR's early history included several foreign manufacturers, such as [[Aston Martin]], [[Austin-Healey]], [[Citro\u00ebn]], [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]], [[MG Cars|MG]], [[Morgan Motor Company|Morgan]], [[Porsche]], [[Renault]], and [[Volkswagen]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Magrath |first=Mike |url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/Columns/articleId=119633 |title=NASCAR Fans, Be Careful When You Talk \"Tradition\" |publisher=Edmunds.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> At a 1954 road race in [[Linden, New Jersey]], Jaguar cars finished first, fourth, fifth and sixth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=db-statswatkinsglen081006&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=Statistically Speaking: Road warriors - NASCAR - Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nAs a matter of policy, NASCAR restricted entry to American car makers from the 1960s until 2004, when [[Toyota]] was allowed to enter the NASCAR [[Camping World Truck Series|Craftsman Truck Series]] with the [[Toyota Tundra]]. The restriction was relaxed in recognition of the fact that the Tundra, while Japanese in origin, is built in the United States.  Commentators have also noted that the \"American\" cars are often built or assembled in Canada and Mexico. As of the 2019 season and the introduction of the Gen-6 car, all of the cars including, the Chevrolet Camaro, Toyota Camry and Ford Mustang are assembled in the United States. Some fans have complained about the entry of a foreign manufacturer into what is perceived as an American sport, while drivers and owners have expressed concern that Toyota's deep pockets, and stated willingness to spend, may increase costs for other teams as well.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-toyota&prov=ap&type=lgns A year after disastrous start, Toyota making inroads at Daytona - NASCAR - Yahoo! Sports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215235730/http://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-toyota&prov=ap&type=lgns |date=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> Also, since NASCAR vehicles are [[Silhouette racing car|only painted to look like production cars]] and are team-built, the \"American-built\" regulation can be considered obsolete.\n\nNASCAR announced in 2006 the addition of Toyota to both the [[Busch Series]] and [[NASCAR Cup Series]] for the 2007 season.  Toyota supported three Cup teams in a total of seven cars in 2007. As of the 2020 season, drivers who compete in the [[Toyota Camry]] include [[Joe Gibbs Racing]] drivers [[Kyle Busch]], [[Martin Truex Jr.]], [[Denny Hamlin]], and [[Erik Jones]]; and [[Leavine Family Racing]] driver [[Christopher Bell (racing driver)|Christopher Bell]].\n\nFour Camrys qualified for and ran in the [[2007 Daytona 500]], becoming the first foreign make to compete in a Cup Series race since the British-made [[MG (car)|MG]] in 1962.  However, Toyota's debut was marred by a [[2007 NASCAR Gatorade Duel Scandal|cheating scandal]] involving owner/driver [[Michael Waltrip]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17136318/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070215193830/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17136318/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-02-15 |title=Apologetic Waltrip nearly quit Daytona - Motor Sports - MSNBC.com |publisher=MSNBC |date=2007-02-16 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nIt should also be noted Dodge, and its parent company Chrysler,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19980507/press012154.html |title=Daimler-Benz and Chrysler Merge |publisher=Theautochannel.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> were owned by Daimler-Benz, a German company, during the period in question when Toyota entered the fray, and is currently held by Fiat, an Italian company.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/06/fiat-to-get-52-of-chrysler-by-paying-500-million-for-treasurys-6/1 | work=USA Today | date=June 3, 2011}}</ref> However, as of 2013\u2013present, Dodge no longer competes in NASCAR (outside of the [[NASCAR Pinty's Series]]), however a possible return has been rumored.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nascar.nbcsports.com/2017/01/31/could-dodge-be-ready-to-return-to-nascar-by-2018-doug-yates-believes-so/ | work=NBC Sports | date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism of tracks==\n\n===Changes in traditional tracks===\n[[Image:Nascarvegas05.jpg|thumb|Las Vegas Motor Speedway]]\nIn 1965 90.9% of the NASCAR schedule was in the South Region of the US and it stayed above 70% until 1989. The Northeast Region started out with a high percentage of races in the early NASCAR years, but from the 1960s until the mid 1980s contained 10% or less of the schedule. The Midwest Region had 21.1% of the races in 1950, but many years before 1970 had no races. The NASCAR schedule had usually contained a few races in the West Region but never more than 10% until the late 1990s. From the late 1990s, and into the early 2000s, a number of new tracks were built and became part of the NASCAR schedule, in places such as [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]], [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicagoland]], the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex]], the [[Northeastern United States (U.S. Census Bureau)|Northeast]], and the [[Greater Los Angeles Area|Los Angeles area]]. This is part of a publicized trend to make NASCAR a more national sport rather than a regional sport. Today, the South makes up only 50% of the NASCAR schedule, while the Northeast has 19.4%, the Midwest has 16.7%, and the West has 13.9% of the schedule. A consequence of NASCAR maintaining its current 36-race schedule is that the inclusion of these new tracks in the schedule results in some of the more traditional tracks in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]] no longer hosting races. Examples include [[North Wilkesboro Speedway]], which is no longer a part of the NASCAR schedule, and [[North Carolina Speedway]], which held its last Cup race in 2004 after being in operation for nearly 40 years.\n\nTraditionalist fans argue that this slow attrition away from tracks in those states where stock car racing began causes the sport to move away from its roots, and from uniquely styled tracks to those of a more \"cookie-cutter\" design. 36.1% (13 races) of the Races today are on what fans call \"cookie-cutter\" tracks (which include [[Charlotte Motor Speedway|Charlotte]], [[Texas Motor Speedway|Texas]], [[Atlanta Motor Speedway|Atlanta]] since its re-design in mid 1997, [[Las Vegas Motor Speedway|Las Vegas]], [[Michigan International Speedway|Michigan]], [[Auto Club Speedway|California]], [[Kansas Speedway|Kansas]] and [[Chicagoland Speedway|Chicagoland]]), compared to the 12.9% (4 races) in 1996. Before NASCAR cut the number of races down for the 1972 season, tracks under 1 mile made up more than 55% of the races. After the changes for the 1972 season, tracks under 1 mile made up only 29% of the races in 1972 and then had 10 races, around 33% of the races, until the mid 1980s. After losing 2 races at Nashville in 1985 and 2 races at North Wilkesboro after 1996 the NASCAR schedule had only 17.6% of races under 1 mile. Tracks with a length between 0.5 and under 1 mile had the highest percentage of the schedule from NASCAR's first season in 1949 until the mid 1990s when tracks between 1.000\u20131.499 miles equaled them in percentage. Tracks between 1.000\u20131.499 miles had the most races in the late 1990s until 1.5\u20131.999-mile tracks passed them in the early to mid 2000s after the loss of races at Rockingham and Darlington. Today 1.5\u20131.999-mile tracks have over 30% of the races. The counterargument is that these \"traditional\" venues are in markets whose support for racing had long declined \u2013 Darlington failed to sell out races until it was cut to one date in 2005 while North Wilkesboro had no infrastructure and little ability to expand beyond 50,000 seats, and Rockingham failed to sell out its races for over five years.\n\nThe 2008 NASCAR\u2013Detroit meetings also saw two automakers call for the addition of at least two new road races. One of these manufacturers also favored reducing the total number of races by at least four while at the same time increasing the number of road races from its current two to at least four. The most obvious way to achieve these goals would be to reduce the number of tracks that host two events a year.<ref name=Autoextremist/> These demands were rejected.\n\n===Decline of road courses===\n\nSince the seventies, NASCAR has increasingly focused its emphasis on oval courses. Many racing fans consider this a key detriment to NASCAR, deriding drivers and the sport as \"a bunch of hillbillies driving in circles for 3 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/15/golden-tate-says-nascar-drivers-arent-athletes-hears-it-from-racing-fans/ |title=Golden Tate says NASCAR drivers aren't athletes, hears it from racing fans &#124; ProFootballTalk |publisher=Profootballtalk.nbcsports.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> Previously, some races were held on road courses, but by 1990 only two road courses were in use: [[Sonoma Raceway]], and [[Watkins Glen International]]. This can be explained by the decrease in handling ability over the course of the vehicles' development. Also notable is the establishment of NASCAR layouts at Sonoma and Watkins Glen. The former omitted the Carousel section of the layout from 1998 to 2018 while the latter omits the Boot, again due to handling issues. Recently, the [[Xfinity Series]] has begun using [[Road America]], initially due to the loss of the [[Milwaukee Mile]] from its schedule. Starting in 2013 the Xfinity Series began racing at [[Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course]] due to the loss of [[Circuit Gilles Villeneuve]]. In 2013, the [[Camping World Truck Series]] began racing at [[Canadian Tire Motorsports Park]], marking the first time in 13 years the Truck Series visited a road course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorracingnetwork.com/Race-Series/NASCAR-Camping-World-Trucks/News/Articles/2012/11/Canada-to-Host-Truck-Race-in-2013.aspx|title=Canada to Host Truck Race in 2013|work=[[Motor Racing Network]]|date=2012-11-16|accessdate=2013-09-12|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129020037/http://www.motorracingnetwork.com/Race-Series/NASCAR-Camping-World-Trucks/News/Articles/2012/11/Canada-to-Host-Truck-Race-in-2013.aspx|archive-date=2013-01-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAs of 2017 due to the popularity, <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/nascar-cup/news/fans-demand-more-road-courses-and-nascar-knows-it-806401/|title=Fans demand more road courses and NASCAR knows it|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> NASCAR has been adding more road courses to the championship season schedule with races also taking place in rain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news-media/2017/05/23/2018-nascar-schedule-charlotte-playoff-race-road-course/|title=2018 NASCAR schedule: Charlotte playoff race will be on road course|date=23 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackflag.jalopnik.com/nascar-finally-adds-a-road-course-to-the-playoffs-1795486329|title=NASCAR Finally Adds A Road Course To The Playoffs|first=Stef|last=Schrader|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackflag.jalopnik.com/this-wet-nascar-road-course-battle-will-completely-melt-1795811389|title=This Wet NASCAR Road Course Battle Will Completely Melt Your Brain|first=Stef|last=Schrader|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Manipulating the outcome of races and championships==\n[[Image:RacingFlagsJune2007.jpg|thumb|left|The flagman displaying the checkered flag with a complete set of stock car racing flags]]\n\nNASCAR uses [[Caution flag#Yellow flag|caution flags]], triggered by race administrators, in which drivers are limited to certain maneuvers. The general purpose of this event is to reduce risk when track conditions deteriorate (for instance, if there is debris on the track, one or more cars crash and emergency vehicles and tow trucks need to be on track, or a car spins and is given the opportunity to catch up with the field).  Generally, when a caution occurs, race cars must tightly pack before a restart.\n\nThe number of cautions per race in the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series increased from 7.4 in 2001 to 9.6 in 2007 (an increase of almost 30%), while the number of actual crashes per race has only increased from 5.6 to 6.7 (an increase of about 20%).<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/graphics/nascardata2007/flash.htm USAToday]\"2007 NASCAR Crash Data\" Retrieved Dec. 22, 2007</ref>  This is likely due to increased caution periods for cleaning debris from the track.  In 2015, the number of cautions per race averaged at 8.2, showing a gradual decline since then.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR Cup Series Cautions and Crashes |url=http://promo.espn.com/news/stats/story/_/page/NASCAR-Sprint-Cup-Cautions-and-Crashes |website=Jayski's Silly Season Site |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> Fans and competitors alike speculate whether some of these cautions are used to keep the cars tightly packed in an effort to keep a race close.<ref>{{cite news |title=COLUMN: NASCAR fans are buzzing over debris cautions |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2015/03/23/column-nascar-fans-are-buzzing-over-debris-cautions/70342502/ |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=USA Today (via AP) |date=23 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Matt |title=NASCAR drivers concerned about timing of late cautions in playoff races |url=https://autoweek.com/article/nascar/timing-cautions-during-playoff-races-concern-nascar-drivers |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Autoweek |publisher=Crain Communications}}</ref>  An unnecessary caution at a specific time could affect a driver's strategy and the outcome of the race, while providing a potential opportunity for other drivers to close the gap and prevent a runaway victory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pruett |first1=Marshall |title=NASCAR's Newest Caution Rule Is Mind Bogglingly Ridiculous |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/news/a27947/nascars-caution-countdown-clock/ |website=Road & Track |publisher=Hearst Communications |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, then two-time champion [[Tony Stewart]], on his radio show hosted via [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], said: \"It's like playing God. They can almost dictate the race instead of the drivers doing it\u2026 I don't know that they've run a fair race all year.\"  Stewart also made a comparison to the [[WWE]], which is scripted. NASCAR itself was not flattered by these comments, and stated that Stewart's comments were \"very, very disappointing\" but did not punish Tony Stewart, as there were no rules against criticizing the officiating of a race.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fryer |first1=Jenna |title=Stewart likens NASCAR to wrestling |url=https://journalstar.com/sports/stewart-likens-nascar-to-wrestling/article_7ec56e8a-7e2a-5a54-bb38-2ba8a115bf00.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Lincoln Journal-Star (via AP) |date=24 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn an unrelated interview, driver [[Matt Kenseth]] said, \"There's for sure entertainment cautions, there's no doubt about that, but we're in the entertainment business and you're going to get some of that and group the field every once in a while.\"  Driver and commentator, [[Kyle Petty]], said, \"We're in the entertainment business, if they want to throw a caution every 40 laps to keep everybody bunched up, so the fans have a better experience, more cautions, the better.\"<ref>[http://www.speedtv.com/commentary/37113/ SpeedTv.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110120648/http://www.speedtv.com/commentary/37113/ |date=2008-01-10 }} \"DESPAIN: My Take on Phantom Cautions\" Retrieved Dec. 22, 2007</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, NASCAR came under fire after the 2013 [[Federated Auto Parts 400]] when it was suggested that the race was manipulated by [[Clint Bowyer]] (having already clinched a playoff berth), who was accused of intentionally spinning out in order to slow down the race which had 7 laps to go. By this time, [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]] was in the lead, and holding on to victory would have likely secured a playoff spot. However, a slow pit stop caused Newman to lose momentum, and [[Carl Edwards]] went on to win instead. This allowed for Bowyer's teammate [[Martin Truex Jr.]] to clinch a spot over Newman.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Viv |title=Nascar Investigating Race for Possible Manipulation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/09/sports/autoracing/nascar-investigating-race-for-possible-manipulation.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=8 September 2013}}</ref> Later that week, NASCAR made its decision to penalize Truex Jr. for the incident, which meant that Newman would take his place. In an odd decision, NASCAR also decided to expand the playoff field to 13 instead of the established 12, giving [[Jeff Gordon]] (one of NASCAR's most popular drivers) a spot, with NASCAR stating that Gordon has also been unfairly aggrieved by Bowyer and Truex Jr.'s actions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Nate |title=NASCAR adds Jeff Gordon to expand Chase field to 13 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2013/09/13/chase-sprint-cup-penalties-joey-logano-david-gilliland-jeff-gordon/2811601/ |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |date=13 September 2013}}</ref> Simultaneously, [[Joey Logano]] was accused of receiving illicit help from [[Front Row Motorsports]] in order to secure a playoff spot, and both [[Penske Racing]] and [[Front Row Motorsports]] were placed on probation for the rest of the year as a result, but Logano was allowed to participate in the playoffs that year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Joey Logano had help? |url=http://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/9662535/report-joey-logano-struck-deal-enter-chase |website=ESPN |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[NASCAR rules and regulations]]\n* [[Car of Tomorrow]]\n* [[List of NASCAR race tracks]]\n* [[Smokey Yunick]]\n* [[Start and park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|NASCAR}}\n*[http://www.nascar.com NASCAR.COM] - The Official Site of NASCAR\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081007153634/http://www.popularmechanics.com/automotive/motor_sports/1336277.html NASCAR Technology] - from PopularMechanics.com\n*[http://www.racing-reference.info/index.jsp Results of Every Race in NASCAR History at Racing-Reference.info]\n\n{{NASCAR}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Criticism Of Nascar}}\n[[Category:NASCAR controversies| ]]\n[[Category:Criticisms of companies|NASCAR]]\n[[Category:Criticism of sports]]\n[[Category:Auto racing controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Negative depictions of NASCAR}}\nThe '''National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing (NASCAR)''' is the sanctioning body for the [[NASCAR Cup Series]], the [[Xfinity Series]] and the [[Gander RV & Outdoors Truck Series]].  [[NASCAR]] also administers a number of [[NASCAR Home Tracks|regional racing series]], including the [[Whelen Modified Tour]], and the [[Whelen All-American Series]], as well as international series in [[NASCAR Pinty's Series|Canada]], [[NASCAR Mexico Series|Mexico]], and [[NASCAR Whelen Euro Series|Europe]].\n\nSimilar to other professional motor racing leagues and sanctioning bodies, NASCAR has been a target of criticism on a variety of issues.  Some critics note the significant differences between present day NASCAR vehicles and true \"[[stock car]]s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.nascar.com/madcowracing/blog/2010/03/03/the_real_reason_nascar_is_less_stock|title=News & Media|accessdate=30 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008133306/http://community.nascar.com/madcowracing/blog/2010/03/03/the_real_reason_nascar_is_less_stock|archive-date=8 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Another topic of debate has been NASCAR's move to larger markets; in 1997, NASCAR added the [[Auto Club Speedway|California]] and [[Texas Motor Speedway]], respectively located in the metro areas of [[Los Angeles]] and [[Dallas]].  This caused NASCAR to move away from traditional tracks such as [[Rockingham Speedway|Rockingham]], which has led to some fans feeling that NASCAR abandoned its core market.<ref>{{cite web |last1=D'Eletto |first1=James |title=NASCAR: North Wilkesboro and Other Forgotten Tracks of the Sport |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1046666-nascar-north-wilkesboro-and-other-forgotten-tracks-of-the-sport |website=Bleacher Report |publisher=WarnerMedia |accessdate=29 March 2019 |language=English |date=1 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carlton |first1=Chuck |title=Is NASCAR losing traditional fan base? |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/635200575/Is-NASCAR-losing-traditional-fan-base.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Deseret News (via The Dallas Morning News) |publisher=Deseret News Publishing |date=16 April 2006 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|igP1Q-KMO6U&t=|\"The Rise and Fall of NASCAR\"}}</ref>\n\nOthers cite the dominance of the [[France family]] (and [[Brian France]] in particular) in NASCAR's business structure, policies, and decision making.  Recently, the increased number of Cup drivers competing consistently in the [[Xfinity Series]] races has been hotly debated. NASCAR has been challenged on the types and frequency of [[Caution flag#Yellow flag|caution flags]], with some critics suggesting the outcome of races is being manipulated,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autoracingsport.com/skinner-joins-stewart-in-exposing-nascar-manipulation/ |title=Skinner joins Stewart in exposing NASCAR manipulation |publisher=Autoracingsport.com |accessdate=2012-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224232432/http://autoracingsport.com/skinner-joins-stewart-in-exposing-nascar-manipulation/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/377065-jimmie-johnson-and-jeff-gordon-did-nascar-manipulate-phoenix-results|title=Jimmie Johnson and Jeff Gordon: Did NASCAR Manipulate Phoenix Results?|first=David|last=Yeazell|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://autoracingsport.com/we-want-your-vote-does-nascar-manipulate-its-races-in-any-way/ |title=Does NASCAR manipulate its races in any way? |publisher=Autoracingsport.com |accessdate=2012-08-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224232437/http://autoracingsport.com/we-want-your-vote-does-nascar-manipulate-its-races-in-any-way/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref> and that the intention is not safety, as NASCAR claims, but closer racing.\n\nSince its peak in 2005, NASCAR has seen a gradual decline, with its TV viewership reaching record lows in 2018<ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR 2018 TV Ratings |url=http://www.espn.com/jayski/pages/story/_/id/22408275/nascar-2018-tv-ratings |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=28 November 2018}}</ref> and race day attendance suffering to record lows as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pockrass |first1=Bob |title=NASCAR teams get creative with sponsors following dip in ratings, attendance |url=http://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/24263283/nascar-checking-speedway-motorsports-inc-earnings-attendance-ratings-first-half-2018-season |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=2 August 2018}}</ref> Reasons cited for its decline include the aforementioned track changes, the introduction of the [[Car of Tomorrow]] which both drivers and fans alike criticized,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Car Of Tomorrow Fuzzy Math And Fuzzier Logic|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/MD80891/84436|magazine=[[Sporting News]]|accessdate=15 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212090228/http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/MD80891/84436|archivedate=2009-02-12|date=May 18, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |title=Postrace comments on 2008 Best Buy 400 |access-date=2019-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312102706/http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |archive-date=2016-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015>{{cite web|last1=Turner|first1=Jared|title=Brian France reveals his biggest failure as NASCAR chairman|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nascar/story/brian-france-nascar-chairman-biggest-failure-car-of-tomorrow-032015|website=[[Fox Sports]]|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|accessdate=22 March 2015|date=March 20, 2015}}</ref> the constant tinkering of the rules of its championship and the racing itself,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jacobs |first1=Christopher |title=NASCAR Is Ruining Stock Car Racing, One Rule Change At a Time |url=https://thefederalist.com/2017/02/24/nascar-ruining-stock-car-racing-one-rule-change-time/ |website=The Federalist |publisher=FDRLST Media |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=24 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Caldwell |first1=Dave |title=NASCAR Fans Are Racing Away From The Sport Even Faster |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davecaldwell/2018/05/02/stock-car-fans-continue-racing-away-from-nascar/#64bb5b3a1df5 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes Media, LLC |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=2 May 2018}}</ref> the change in its race day experience,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gluck |first1=Jeff |title=Fans explain why they stopped attending NASCAR races |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2016/07/01/nascar-fans-attendance-cost/86587042/ |website=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> the perceived decline in the quality of its racing,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fryer |first1=Jenna |title=NASCAR tries to end slide with push for more exciting racing |url=https://wlos.com/sports/content/nascar-tries-to-end-slide-with-push-for-more-exciting-racing |accessdate=29 March 2019 |publisher=ABC 13 WLOS}}</ref> and the retirement of its past stars.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruce |first1=Kenny |title=How a retiring star exposed NASCAR's |url=https://www.autosport.com/nascar/feature/8245/how-a-retiring-star-exposed-nascar-big-problem |website=Autosport |publisher=Motorsport Network |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR needs new stars and Kyle Larson may save the sport |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2019/02/01/nascar-needs-new-stars-and-kyle-larson-may-save-the-sport/38989823/ |website=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnother general area of criticism, not only of NASCAR, but other [[motorsport]]s as well, includes questions about [[Gasoline|fuel]] consumption,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mndaily.com/2008/06/04/nascar-waste-resources |title=NASCAR a waste of resources |publisher=Mndaily.com |date=2008-06-04 |accessdate=2012-08-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319224928/http://www.mndaily.com/2008/06/04/nascar-waste-resources |archive-date=2012-03-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Exhaust gas|emission]]s, [[engine]] [[decibels|noise levels]], and [[air pollutants|pollution]], and the use of [[Tetraethyllead|lead additives]] in the [[gasoline]].\n\n==The [[Car of Tomorrow]] and changes in stock car style==\n[[Image:KennyWallace2006Car.jpg|thumb|[[Mark McFarland]] (88) spins at [[Bristol Motor Speedway]], while [[Kenny Wallace]] (22) and [[Ashton Lewis Jr.]] (25) pass to the inside during a [[Busch Series]] event in 2006, using Gen-4 cars.]]\n[[File:Dodge Charger NASCAR (Montreal).jpg|thumb|left|The Car of Tomorrow model on display in January 2008. Drivers and fans alike criticized the aesthetics of the car, and some have cited the Car of Tomorrow for contributing to the decline of NASCAR.]]\nBeginning in the early 2000s, NASCAR researched and worked on a new model to introduce towards the end of the decade. One particular area of scrutiny was driver safety; [[Dale Earnhardt]] [[Death of Dale Earnhardt|fatally crashed]] at the [[2001 Daytona 500]], and the safety of the cars used at the time was questioned.\n\nThe Car of Tomorrow was first tested in December 2005, and was first revealed to the public in 2006, with numerous safety improvements being touted. The Car of Tomorrow made its debut at the [[2007 Food City 500]], and was almost immediately criticized by both fans and drivers alike. Many fans disliked the large and boxy design, its more generic appearance and the use of a detached wing.<ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015/> [[Kyle Busch]], who won the first race using the model, proclaimed that the car \"sucks\" after his victory and expanded on this criticism at Dover in 2008 by noting how the CoT was \"hitting a wall of air\" in the wake of a leading car, thus neutralizing ability to close up on leaders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |title=Postrace comments on 2008 Best Buy 400 |access-date=2019-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312102706/http://independenttribune.net/index.php/sports/jnowcomments/so_just_how_might_a_head_to_head_duel_go_between_dale_earnhardt_sr_and_kyle |archive-date=2016-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Busch was not the only driver to vent his frustrations; [[Jeff Gordon]] was also critical of the car, stating after the [[2007 Lenox Industrial Tools 300|2007 New England 300]], \"I'd like to know who it was who said this car would reduce the [[aerodynamics|aero]] [[understeer|push]] because I could have told you from when I first drove this car that it would be worse.\"<ref>[http://monkeesfan.blogspot.com/2007/07/plenty-of-subplots-at-hew-hampshire.html Plenty Of Subplots At New Hampshire]</ref>\n\nDespite the criticism, NASCAR fully implemented the model in [[2008 in NASCAR|2008]], and overall brought dramatic safety improvements and reduced costs of car maintenance.<ref name=ESPN-CoT-Thanks-for-the-memories>{{cite web|last1=McGee|first1=Ryan|title=Thanks for the memories, CoT|url=http://espn.go.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/8950107/nascar-car-tomorrow-buried-praised|website=[[ESPN|espn.go.com]]|publisher=[[ESPN]], [[ESPN The Magazine]]|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=February 15, 2013}}</ref> Despite the overall safety improvements, one point of contention was that the rear wing increased the severity of on-track accidents by causing cars to be more prone to flipping over or going airborne at higher speeds. After 3 such incidents between 2007 and 2010, NASCAR switched to a more traditional rear spoiler instead.<ref name=ESPN-CoT-Thanks-for-the-memories/>\n\nIn a retrospective interview in 2015, Brian France believed that the introduction of the model as his biggest failure, due to the lack of manufacturer identity, as well as its perceived effects on its racing.<ref name=Fox-BrianFrance-CoT-2015 /><ref name=Freep-BrianFranceCoT-2015>{{cite news|last1=Brudenell|first1=Mike|title=NASCAR top executive in Detroit: We'll 'make mistakes': NASCAR CEO and chairman Brian France speaks at Detroit Economic Club in Dearborn today to high schoolers and college students.|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/motor/2015/03/19/nascar-brian-france-detroit-economic-club/25044179/|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|accessdate=15 August 2015|date=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Even after the implementation of the [[Generation 6 (NASCAR)|Generation 6]] model, some fans still cite the Car of Tomorrow for causing the decline of NASCAR. Writer Christopher Smith of Car Throttle wrote that, \"...Nascar rules pretty much require all the race cars to be the same - no individuality aside from stickers that differentiate the models. Nascar television ratings and fan interest has been decreasing for years, and as far as I\u2019m concerned, this is the main reason.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Christopher |title=The Cars That Ruined Nascar, And How There's Hope For The Future |url=https://www.carthrottle.com/post/the-cars-that-ruined-nascar-and-how-theres-hope-for-the-future/ |website=Car Throttle |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Gen-6 cars themselves, while somewhat better received than the Car of Tomorrow (Generation 5) cars were at the time, have received some blow-back. [[Denny Hamlin]] was most critical, saying, \"I don't want to be the pessimist, but it did not race as good as our generation 5 or regular [[Car of Tomorrow|CoT]] cars did.\" Hamlin received a $25,000 fine for his comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar-news/4483224-denny-hamlin-fine-critical-comments-sprint-cup-car-gen-6-racing-phoenix|title=Denny Hamlin fined $25,000 for criticizing new Sprint Cup car, racing at Phoenix|date=March 7, 2013|author=Pockrass, Bob|work=Sporting News|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Engine noise levels==\nIn 2007, a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article cited two studies conducted by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]], conducted during races at [[Bristol Motor Speedway]] in 2005, which found that engine noise levels can reach as high as 140 [[decibels]], which can do severe damage to a person's sense of hearing. One NIOSH engineer stated that 43 cars during a race was \"equivalent to a jet engine\". The first study focused exclusively on Bristol Motor Speedway, while the second study took other NASCAR race tracks into account, and both studies found that noise levels regularly exceeded 140 decibels when the race cars were accelerating at full throttle, and that the noise levels lasted, on average, about three to four hours, the average duration of a NASCAR race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/26/sports/othersports/26noise.html|title=The Sound and the Fury, and Possibly the Danger|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 26, 2007}}</ref> The article cites 7-time NASCAR Cup Series champion [[Richard Petty]], as well as other drivers such as [[Jeff Burton]], now requiring the use of [[hearing aids]] due to hearing loss caused by engine noise. According to the article, a NIOSH engineer suggested putting mufflers on the cars in order to reduce the noise, but a NASCAR spokesperson stated that they already tried that in the 1960s, and it did not work as intended.\n\n==Business structure and decision-making policies==\nSince its founding in 1947 by [[William France Sr.]], the overall NASCAR organization has been majority owned by the France family, ensuring that the family controls a majority of the revenue that the sport generates. NASCAR is also criticized for its reluctance to promote some aspects of safety that it would have to pay for (''e.g.'', traveling safety crew),<ref>[http://cbs.sportsline.com/b/page/pressbox/0,1328,3544996,00.html CBS Sportsline.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017013734/http://cbs.sportsline.com/b/page/pressbox/0%2C1328%2C3544996%2C00.html |date=October 17, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/mld/kansascity/sports/motorsports/14558242.htm|title=KC Breaking News, Sports, Weather & More - KansasCity.com & The Kansas City Star|website=www.kansascity.com|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> and other allegedly monopolistic aspects such as merchandising and race-track ownership.\n\nIn addition, due to its influence and lack of drivers' say, NASCAR has been described as a \"benevolent dictatorship,\" with a top-heavy command structure that tends to keep dissenters in line.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Keefe |first=Brian |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/09/05/8271412/index.htm |title=CNN Money Magazine (online) |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2005-09-05 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/nascar/2005-06-20-nascar-debacle_x.htm USA Today], June 20, 2005</ref> Examples of such influence included the cancellation of the [[Speed Channel]] television show ''[[Pit Bull (TV series)|Pit Bull]]'' (which frequently criticized many of NASCAR's decisions and policies and enjoyed modest ratings), frequent use of the vague \"detrimental to NASCAR\" rule, and the creation of rules on whim, especially during a race. NASCAR has taken to penalizing drivers in recent years, with fines, point penalties, and lap penalties in races for drivers or mechanics who use obscene language in interviews to the media.<ref>[http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/05/092305Poe.asp SpeedWayMedia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213033559/http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/05/092305Poe.asp |date=December 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBecause of Fox Sports' heavy affiliation with NASCAR, a fair amount of the network's programming is NASCAR-related.\n\n==Driver competition in multiple series==\n[[File:KyleBuschToyotaMilwaukeeMile2009.jpg|thumb|right|2009 Nationwide Series car of Cup Series regular [[Kyle Busch]], who won the Nationwide Series championship that year]]\nNASCAR has long allowed drivers to compete in as many series and events as they like, with few restrictions. However, in recent years, many Cup Series drivers have competed in and dominated the lower tier Xfinity Series races on a regular basis, earning Cup drivers the nickname \"[[Buschwhacker]]s\" (derived from the 1984\u20132007 sponsorship of NASCAR's second-highest series by [[Busch Beer]]). The situation is compounded by the close timing of the races in the two series: a typical NASCAR weekend has a Xfinity race on Saturday followed by a Cup race on Sunday at the same track. Some have wondered why \"major league\" Cup drivers are allowed to compete in the \"minor league\" races with such frequency, and whether Xfinity is an adequate developmental series. Sportswriter Bob Margolis noted that much of this is due to the similarities between the cars used in the two series (they are mostly alike except for the engines and the wheelbase), and the desire for Cup drivers to get as much practice time as possible to learn about the track and car setup before the main race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=bm-buschpreview021706&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=Sports.Yahoo.com |publisher=Sports.Yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nIn the aforementioned 2008 meetings between NASCAR and Detroit automakers, the automakers also called for the Xfinity Series to become strictly a developmental series, with Cup drivers prohibited from running in the junior series.<ref name=Autoextremist>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoextremist.com/fumes1/2008/8/4/fumes-457.html |title=Fumes #457 \u2013 The Detroit Three get down to the business of NASCAR |first=Peter M. |last=De Lorenzo |publisher=Autoextremist.com |date=2008-08-06 |accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref>  The request was rejected at that time. However, in late 2010, media reports began to indicate that NASCAR may institute a slightly modified version of this rule for 2011, with Cup drivers allowed to run in Xfinity races but not to compete for the series championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/nascar/cup/columns/story?columnist=blount_terry&id=5842177 |title=The best and worst of 2010 |first=Terry |last=Blount |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 23, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> In January 2011, ''NASCAR.com'' confirmed this, adding that drivers will now be allowed to compete for the championship in only one national series in a given season, a change that also affects the [[Camping World Truck Series|Truck Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news/110110/rule-change-drivers-one-championship/index.html |title=NASCAR drivers must elect championships in '11 |first=Dave |last=Rodman |publisher=NASCAR.com |date=January 11, 2011 |accessdate=January 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlthough many claim that the added track time gained by running a Xfinity or Truck Series race helps drivers during the Cup Series race, any positive effects are not seen in final championship standings. For example, during his run of 5 consecutive Cup Series Championships, [[Jimmie Johnson]] ran only 3 Busch/Nationwide races in 2006, 1 each in 2007 and 2008, and none in 2009 or 2010. Another example is the 2009 season, where [[Kyle Busch]] won the [[2009 NASCAR Nationwide Series|Nationwide Series]] championship but failed to qualify for the 2009 [[NASCAR Chase for the Championship|Cup Series Chase]].\n\nOn October 2016, NASCAR announced new participation guidelines for its three national series, limiting the amount of Xfinity Series and Truck Series races that full-time drivers in its premier series will be allowed to compete in, starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/en_us/news-media/articles/2016/10/26/2017-limitations-sprint-cup-drivers-xfinity-truck-series-races.html |title=New participation guidelines put limits in place for 2017 |first=Zack |last=Albert |publisher=NASCAR.com |date=October 26, 2016 |accessdate=October 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental effects==\n\n===Fuel consumption===\n[[File:SunocoDispenserRoadAmerica2010Bucyros200.jpg|thumb|right|NASCAR fuel supply truck in 2010]]\nAccording to NASCAR, about 6,000 U.S. gallons (~23 kilolitres) of fuel are consumed during a typical Cup Series weekend.<ref name = \"Finney\">{{cite web | first = Mike | last = Finney | title = Like the cars, fuel goes fast in NASCAR | publisher = The (Wilmington, Del.) News Journal | date = January 2, 2006 | url = http://www.azcentral.com/sports/speed/articles/0602nascargas-ON.html | work = AZCentral.com | accessdate = 2007-11-19}}</ref> For the 2006 season, which included 36 points races, the total for the season would have been 216,000 U.S. gallons (818 kilolitres).\nOne environmental critic recently estimated NASCAR's total fuel consumption across all series at 2 million U.S. gallons (7,570 kilolitres) of gas for one season.<ref name = \"E\">{{cite web | first = Jean | last = Gerard | title = Motor Madness: Gas Guzzling is Business as Usual at NASCAR | publisher = E/The Environmental Magazine | url = http://www.emagazine.com/view/?2947&printview | accessdate = 2007-11-18 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927213046/http://www.emagazine.com/view/?2947&printview | archive-date = 2007-09-27 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nAt race speeds, Cup Series cars get 2 to 5 miles per gallon.<ref name = \"Finney\" /><ref name = \"E\" /><ref>{{cite web|first=Natale |last=Servino |title=NASCAR goes green? New tracks touted as good for the planet |publisher=Earth Island Journal |url=http://www.earthisland.org/EIJOURNAL/new_articles.cfm?articleID=981&journalID=84 |accessdate=2007-11-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013133428/http://earthisland.org/EIJOURNAL/new_articles.cfm?articleID=981&journalID=84 |archivedate=2007-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Consumption under caution can be estimated at 14-18 mpg, based on comparable engines generally available to the public. The ''rate'' of fuel consumption tends to be the same regardless of the actual speeds of the cars, as teams change gear ratios for each race to ensure that the engine always operates in its optimum power band; however, the fuel ''mileage'' will vary for each race, depending on the maximum speeds attained.\n\nThe fuel consumption criticism dates to 1974 and the [[1973 oil crisis|energy crisis]]; NASCAR responded by showing data that racing was far less consumptive of fuel than regular air travel, etc.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n===Emissions and pollution===\nThe consumption figures above provide no insight on environmental impact in terms of emissions. NASCAR vehicles are generally unregulated by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]], and in particular, they have no mufflers, catalytic converters or other emissions control devices. However, some local short tracks which run under NASCAR sanction require certain emissions control devices. Many short tracks run mufflers in compliance with noise ordinances at some tracks; in the early years of the [[Camping World Truck Series]], some races were held at venues which required mufflers, a requirement still used in NASCAR's K&N Pro Series (East and West) and Whelen (North and South) Modified Tours.\n\nNASCAR continued to use [[Unleaded gasoline#Lead|lead additives]] in its race gasoline until the [[2007 Auto Club 500]] at [[California Speedway]] on February 25,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scenedaily.com/stories/2006/10/16/scene_daily394.html |title=Nextel Cup going to unleaded fuel in 2007 |accessdate=2007-06-17 |author=Bob Passrock |date=October 21, 2006 |work=scenedaily.com}}</ref> which led to concerns about the health of those exposed to the fumes of the cars (fans and residents living near the race tracks). Lead is a well-known environmental risk, but the performance needs of race engines (in particular, the high [[Compression Ratio|compression ratios]] and sustained/repeated operation at high rpm and load) once made it difficult to switch to un[[Tetraethyllead|leaded fuel]].\n\nIn the United States, the commercial use of leaded fuel has been phased out since the early 1970s, when catalytic converters were required to be installed on new cars, making unleaded fuel a requirement (leaded fuel will destroy a [[catalytic converter]]). The sale of leaded fuel has been mostly banned in the US since 1996, but exemptions exist for auto racing, aircraft, farm and marine equipment.\n\nNASCAR eventually took steps to eliminate the need for leaded fuels. In 1998, NASCAR and then-fuel supplier [[Tosco Corporation|Tosco]] (Now [[ConocoPhillips]], the company that produces the [[Union 76]] brand of fuel) conducted an unsuccessful test of unleaded fuel in selected Busch Series races. In July 2006, in the first in a four-week test run of unleaded fuel, the first race since 1998 to run unleaded gasoline, known as [[Sunoco]] 260 GT Plus, a commercially available racing fuel, was held during a Busch race at the [[Gateway International Raceway]] in [[Madison, Illinois]]. The testing in July 2006 was successful with no suspected engine failures or malfunctions from the new fuel. In October 2006, NASCAR stated its intention to transition to unleaded fuel in all three top series (Craftsman, Busch and Cup) in 2007, starting with the [[Auto Club 500]].\n\nDuring the first race in which unleaded fuel was used, there were a number of engine failures during the race, leading many to believe that the unleaded fuel is to be blamed.  The drivers who encountered failures include [[Dale Earnhardt, Jr.]] and [[Martin Truex Jr.]] of [[Dale Earnhardt, Inc.]] and [[Kasey Kahne]] of [[Evernham Motorsports]]. The engine failures of both Earnhardt and Truex were attributed in part to the lack of a lead additive, but also to centrifugal force causing improper distribution of oil between the left and right sides of the engine. Evernham Motorsports has not disclosed the reason behind Kahne's engine failure.\n\nThe 2008 season marked the first season all 36 races used unleaded racing fuel.\n\n2011 marked one of the largest \u201cgreen initiatives\u201d in the fifty plus year history of NASCAR when all fuel sources were to include Ethanol in a blend called E15.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Rodman, NASCAR.COM |url=http://www.nascar.com/news/110122/ethanol-details-thunder/index.html |title=Fill 'er up: Teams off and running with E15 fuel - Jan 22, 2011 |publisher=Nascar.Com |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>  One unintended consequence of the conversion was higher horsepower and therefore slightly lower fuel economy.  It is argued however, that the reduction in fuel economy and the resultant increase in fuel use may offset any environmental impact savings by reduced emissions.  Although not connected to the fuel blend, a new \u201cDry Break\u201d self-venting fuel supply can was also adopted in part for safety (reduced the number of people working on the racecar during a pit stop) but also in part to reduce the amount of fuel spilled during a pit stop, which has both environmental and safety implications.  The reduced fuel spillage is negligible at best when observing a pit stop as fuel spills are common and during competition there is no real method to determine with any certainty the volume of fuel lost.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\nIn 2012 a complete technology change and shift in thinking occurred when NASCAR switched the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series to [[Fuel injection in NASCAR|fuel injection]] from the current carburetor. Arguments have been made about increased efficiency; however, race teams will work to ensure they take advantage of the additional horsepower and efficiency to increase speeds so any improvement in efficiency may be lost to competition.\n\n==Participation of non-American manufacturers==\n[[Image:Auto Show 067.jpg|thumb|left|A Gen-5 car body with [[Toyota Camry]] decals.]]\nNASCAR's early history included several foreign manufacturers, such as [[Aston Martin]], [[Austin-Healey]], [[Citro\u00ebn]], [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]], [[MG Cars|MG]], [[Morgan Motor Company|Morgan]], [[Porsche]], [[Renault]], and [[Volkswagen]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Magrath |first=Mike |url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/Columns/articleId=119633 |title=NASCAR Fans, Be Careful When You Talk \"Tradition\" |publisher=Edmunds.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> At a 1954 road race in [[Linden, New Jersey]], Jaguar cars finished first, fourth, fifth and sixth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=db-statswatkinsglen081006&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=Statistically Speaking: Road warriors - NASCAR - Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nAs a matter of policy, NASCAR restricted entry to American car makers from the 1960s until 2004, when [[Toyota]] was allowed to enter the NASCAR [[Camping World Truck Series|Craftsman Truck Series]] with the [[Toyota Tundra]]. The restriction was relaxed in recognition of the fact that the Tundra, while Japanese in origin, is built in the United States.  Commentators have also noted that the \"American\" cars are often built or assembled in Canada and Mexico. As of the 2019 season and the introduction of the Gen-6 car, all of the cars including, the Chevrolet Camaro, Toyota Camry and Ford Mustang are assembled in the United States. Some fans have complained about the entry of a foreign manufacturer into what is perceived as an American sport, while drivers and owners have expressed concern that Toyota's deep pockets, and stated willingness to spend, may increase costs for other teams as well.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-toyota&prov=ap&type=lgns A year after disastrous start, Toyota making inroads at Daytona - NASCAR - Yahoo! Sports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215235730/http://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-toyota&prov=ap&type=lgns |date=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> Also, since NASCAR vehicles are [[Silhouette racing car|only painted to look like production cars]] and are team-built, the \"American-built\" regulation can be considered obsolete.\n\nNASCAR announced in 2006 the addition of Toyota to both the [[Busch Series]] and [[NASCAR Cup Series]] for the 2007 season.  Toyota supported three Cup teams in a total of seven cars in 2007. As of the 2020 season, drivers who compete in the [[Toyota Camry]] include [[Joe Gibbs Racing]] drivers [[Kyle Busch]], [[Martin Truex Jr.]], [[Denny Hamlin]], and [[Erik Jones]]; and [[Leavine Family Racing]] driver [[Christopher Bell (racing driver)|Christopher Bell]].\n\nFour Camrys qualified for and ran in the [[2007 Daytona 500]], becoming the first foreign make to compete in a Cup Series race since the British-made [[MG (car)|MG]] in 1962.  However, Toyota's debut was marred by a [[2007 NASCAR Gatorade Duel Scandal|cheating scandal]] involving owner/driver [[Michael Waltrip]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17136318/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070215193830/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17136318/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-02-15 |title=Apologetic Waltrip nearly quit Daytona - Motor Sports - MSNBC.com |publisher=MSNBC |date=2007-02-16 |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref>\n\nIt should also be noted Dodge, and its parent company Chrysler,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19980507/press012154.html |title=Daimler-Benz and Chrysler Merge |publisher=Theautochannel.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> were owned by Daimler-Benz, a German company, during the period in question when Toyota entered the fray, and is currently held by Fiat, an Italian company.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/06/fiat-to-get-52-of-chrysler-by-paying-500-million-for-treasurys-6/1 | work=USA Today | date=June 3, 2011}}</ref> However, as of 2013\u2013present, Dodge no longer competes in NASCAR (outside of the [[NASCAR Pinty's Series]]), however a possible return has been rumored.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nascar.nbcsports.com/2017/01/31/could-dodge-be-ready-to-return-to-nascar-by-2018-doug-yates-believes-so/ | work=NBC Sports | date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism of tracks==\n\n===Changes in traditional tracks===\n[[Image:Nascarvegas05.jpg|thumb|Las Vegas Motor Speedway]]\nIn 1965 90.9% of the NASCAR schedule was in the South Region of the US and it stayed above 70% until 1989. The Northeast Region started out with a high percentage of races in the early NASCAR years, but from the 1960s until the mid 1980s contained 10% or less of the schedule. The Midwest Region had 21.1% of the races in 1950, but many years before 1970 had no races. The NASCAR schedule had usually contained a few races in the West Region but never more than 10% until the late 1990s. From the late 1990s, and into the early 2000s, a number of new tracks were built and became part of the NASCAR schedule, in places such as [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]], [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicagoland]], the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex]], the [[Northeastern United States (U.S. Census Bureau)|Northeast]], and the [[Greater Los Angeles Area|Los Angeles area]]. This is part of a publicized trend to make NASCAR a more national sport rather than a regional sport. Today, the South makes up only 50% of the NASCAR schedule, while the Northeast has 19.4%, the Midwest has 16.7%, and the West has 13.9% of the schedule. A consequence of NASCAR maintaining its current 36-race schedule is that the inclusion of these new tracks in the schedule results in some of the more traditional tracks in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]] no longer hosting races. Examples include [[North Wilkesboro Speedway]], which is no longer a part of the NASCAR schedule, and [[North Carolina Speedway]], which held its last Cup race in 2004 after being in operation for nearly 40 years.\n\nTraditionalist fans argue that this slow attrition away from tracks in those states where stock car racing began causes the sport to move away from its roots, and from uniquely styled tracks to those of a more \"cookie-cutter\" design. 36.1% (13 races) of the Races today are on what fans call \"cookie-cutter\" tracks (which include [[Charlotte Motor Speedway|Charlotte]], [[Texas Motor Speedway|Texas]], [[Atlanta Motor Speedway|Atlanta]] since its re-design in mid 1997, [[Las Vegas Motor Speedway|Las Vegas]], [[Michigan International Speedway|Michigan]], [[Auto Club Speedway|California]], [[Kansas Speedway|Kansas]] and [[Chicagoland Speedway|Chicagoland]]), compared to the 12.9% (4 races) in 1996. Before NASCAR cut the number of races down for the 1972 season, tracks under 1 mile made up more than 55% of the races. After the changes for the 1972 season, tracks under 1 mile made up only 29% of the races in 1972 and then had 10 races, around 33% of the races, until the mid 1980s. After losing 2 races at Nashville in 1985 and 2 races at North Wilkesboro after 1996 the NASCAR schedule had only 17.6% of races under 1 mile. Tracks with a length between 0.5 and under 1 mile had the highest percentage of the schedule from NASCAR's first season in 1949 until the mid 1990s when tracks between 1.000\u20131.499 miles equaled them in percentage. Tracks between 1.000\u20131.499 miles had the most races in the late 1990s until 1.5\u20131.999-mile tracks passed them in the early to mid 2000s after the loss of races at Rockingham and Darlington. Today 1.5\u20131.999-mile tracks have over 30% of the races. The counterargument is that these \"traditional\" venues are in markets whose support for racing had long declined \u2013 Darlington failed to sell out races until it was cut to one date in 2005 while North Wilkesboro had no infrastructure and little ability to expand beyond 50,000 seats, and Rockingham failed to sell out its races for over five years.\n\nThe 2008 NASCAR\u2013Detroit meetings also saw two automakers call for the addition of at least two new road races. One of these manufacturers also favored reducing the total number of races by at least four while at the same time increasing the number of road races from its current two to at least four. The most obvious way to achieve these goals would be to reduce the number of tracks that host two events a year.<ref name=Autoextremist/> These demands were rejected.\n\n===Decline of road courses===\n\nSince the seventies, NASCAR has increasingly focused its emphasis on oval courses. Many racing fans consider this a key detriment to NASCAR, deriding drivers and the sport as \"a bunch of hillbillies driving in circles for 3 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/15/golden-tate-says-nascar-drivers-arent-athletes-hears-it-from-racing-fans/ |title=Golden Tate says NASCAR drivers aren't athletes, hears it from racing fans &#124; ProFootballTalk |publisher=Profootballtalk.nbcsports.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-03}}</ref> Previously, some races were held on road courses, but by 1990 only two road courses were in use: [[Sonoma Raceway]], and [[Watkins Glen International]]. This can be explained by the decrease in handling ability over the course of the vehicles' development. Also notable is the establishment of NASCAR layouts at Sonoma and Watkins Glen. The former omitted the Carousel section of the layout from 1998 to 2018 while the latter omits the Boot, again due to handling issues. Recently, the [[Xfinity Series]] has begun using [[Road America]], initially due to the loss of the [[Milwaukee Mile]] from its schedule. Starting in 2013 the Xfinity Series began racing at [[Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course]] due to the loss of [[Circuit Gilles Villeneuve]]. In 2013, the [[Camping World Truck Series]] began racing at [[Canadian Tire Motorsports Park]], marking the first time in 13 years the Truck Series visited a road course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorracingnetwork.com/Race-Series/NASCAR-Camping-World-Trucks/News/Articles/2012/11/Canada-to-Host-Truck-Race-in-2013.aspx|title=Canada to Host Truck Race in 2013|work=[[Motor Racing Network]]|date=2012-11-16|accessdate=2013-09-12|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129020037/http://www.motorracingnetwork.com/Race-Series/NASCAR-Camping-World-Trucks/News/Articles/2012/11/Canada-to-Host-Truck-Race-in-2013.aspx|archive-date=2013-01-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAs of 2017 due to the popularity, <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/nascar-cup/news/fans-demand-more-road-courses-and-nascar-knows-it-806401/|title=Fans demand more road courses and NASCAR knows it|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> NASCAR has been adding more road courses to the championship season schedule with races also taking place in rain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news-media/2017/05/23/2018-nascar-schedule-charlotte-playoff-race-road-course/|title=2018 NASCAR schedule: Charlotte playoff race will be on road course|date=23 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackflag.jalopnik.com/nascar-finally-adds-a-road-course-to-the-playoffs-1795486329|title=NASCAR Finally Adds A Road Course To The Playoffs|first=Stef|last=Schrader|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackflag.jalopnik.com/this-wet-nascar-road-course-battle-will-completely-melt-1795811389|title=This Wet NASCAR Road Course Battle Will Completely Melt Your Brain|first=Stef|last=Schrader|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Manipulating the outcome of races and championships==\n[[Image:RacingFlagsJune2007.jpg|thumb|left|The flagman displaying the checkered flag with a complete set of stock car racing flags]]\n\nNASCAR uses [[Caution flag#Yellow flag|caution flags]], triggered by race administrators, in which drivers are limited to certain maneuvers. The general purpose of this event is to reduce risk when track conditions deteriorate (for instance, if there is debris on the track, one or more cars crash and emergency vehicles and tow trucks need to be on track, or a car spins and is given the opportunity to catch up with the field).  Generally, when a caution occurs, race cars must tightly pack before a restart.\n\nThe number of cautions per race in the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series increased from 7.4 in 2001 to 9.6 in 2007 (an increase of almost 30%), while the number of actual crashes per race has only increased from 5.6 to 6.7 (an increase of about 20%).<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/graphics/nascardata2007/flash.htm USAToday]\"2007 NASCAR Crash Data\" Retrieved Dec. 22, 2007</ref>  This is likely due to increased caution periods for cleaning debris from the track.  In 2015, the number of cautions per race averaged at 8.2, showing a gradual decline since then.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASCAR Cup Series Cautions and Crashes |url=http://promo.espn.com/news/stats/story/_/page/NASCAR-Sprint-Cup-Cautions-and-Crashes |website=Jayski's Silly Season Site |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> Fans and competitors alike speculate whether some of these cautions are used to keep the cars tightly packed in an effort to keep a race close.<ref>{{cite news |title=COLUMN: NASCAR fans are buzzing over debris cautions |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2015/03/23/column-nascar-fans-are-buzzing-over-debris-cautions/70342502/ |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=USA Today (via AP) |date=23 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Matt |title=NASCAR drivers concerned about timing of late cautions in playoff races |url=https://autoweek.com/article/nascar/timing-cautions-during-playoff-races-concern-nascar-drivers |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Autoweek |publisher=Crain Communications}}</ref>  An unnecessary caution at a specific time could affect a driver\u2019s strategy and the outcome of the race, while providing a potential opportunity for other drivers to close the gap and prevent a runaway victory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pruett |first1=Marshall |title=NASCAR's Newest Caution Rule Is Mind Bogglingly Ridiculous |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/news/a27947/nascars-caution-countdown-clock/ |website=Road & Track |publisher=Hearst Communications |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, then two time champion [[Tony Stewart]], on his radio show hosted via [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], said: \"It's like playing God. They can almost dictate the race instead of the drivers doing it\u2026 I don't know that they've run a fair race all year.\"  Stewart also made a comparison to the [[WWE]], which is scripted. NASCAR itself was not flattered by these comments, and stated that Stewart's comments were \"very, very disappointing\" but did not punish Tony Stewart, as there were no rules against criticizing the officiating of a race.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fryer |first1=Jenna |title=Stewart likens NASCAR to wrestling |url=https://journalstar.com/sports/stewart-likens-nascar-to-wrestling/article_7ec56e8a-7e2a-5a54-bb38-2ba8a115bf00.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=Lincoln Journal-Star (via AP) |date=24 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn an unrelated interview, driver [[Matt Kenseth]] said, \"There's for sure entertainment cautions, there's no doubt about that, but we're in the entertainment business and you're going to get some of that and group the field every once in a while.\"  Driver and commentator, [[Kyle Petty]], said, \"We're in the entertainment business, if they want to throw a caution every 40 laps to keep everybody bunched up, so the fans have a better experience, more cautions, the better.\"<ref>[http://www.speedtv.com/commentary/37113/ SpeedTv.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110120648/http://www.speedtv.com/commentary/37113/ |date=2008-01-10 }} \"DESPAIN: My Take on Phantom Cautions\" Retrieved Dec. 22, 2007</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, NASCAR came under fire after the 2013 [[Federated Auto Parts 400]] when it was suggested that the race was manipulated by [[Clint Bowyer]] (having already clinched a playoff berth), who was accused of intentionally spinning out in order to slow down the race which had 7 laps to go. By this time, [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]] was in the lead, and holding on to victory would have likely secured a playoff spot. However, a slow pit stop caused Newman to lose momentum, and [[Carl Edwards]] went on to win instead. This allowed for Bowyer's teammate [[Martin Truex Jr.]] to clinch a spot over Newman.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Viv |title=Nascar Investigating Race for Possible Manipulation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/09/sports/autoracing/nascar-investigating-race-for-possible-manipulation.html |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=8 September 2013}}</ref> Later that week, NASCAR made its decision to penalize Truex Jr. for the incident, which meant that Newman would take his place. In an odd decision, NASCAR also decided to expand the playoff field to 13 instead of the established 12, giving [[Jeff Gordon]] (one of NASCAR's most popular drivers) a spot, with NASCAR stating that Gordon has also been unfairly aggrieved by Bowyer and Truex Jr.'s actions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Nate |title=NASCAR adds Jeff Gordon to expand Chase field to 13 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2013/09/13/chase-sprint-cup-penalties-joey-logano-david-gilliland-jeff-gordon/2811601/ |accessdate=29 March 2019 |agency=USA Today |publisher=Gannett |date=13 September 2013}}</ref> Simultaneously, [[Joey Logano]] was accused of receiving illicit help from [[Front Row Motorsports]] in order to secure a playoff spot, and both [[Penske Racing]] and [[Front Row Motorsports]] were placed on probation for the rest of the year as a result, but Logano was allowed to participate in the playoffs that year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Joey Logano had help? |url=http://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/9662535/report-joey-logano-struck-deal-enter-chase |website=ESPN |accessdate=29 March 2019 |date=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[NASCAR rules and regulations]]\n* [[Car of Tomorrow]]\n* [[List of NASCAR race tracks]]\n* [[Smokey Yunick]]\n* [[Start and park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|NASCAR}}\n*[http://www.nascar.com NASCAR.COM] - The Official Site of NASCAR\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081007153634/http://www.popularmechanics.com/automotive/motor_sports/1336277.html NASCAR Technology] - from PopularMechanics.com\n*[http://www.racing-reference.info/index.jsp Results of Every Race in NASCAR History at Racing-Reference.info]\n\n{{NASCAR}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Criticism Of Nascar}}\n[[Category:NASCAR controversies| ]]\n[[Category:Criticisms of companies|NASCAR]]\n[[Category:Criticism of sports]]\n[[Category:Auto racing controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManipulating the outcome of races and championships:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: two time \u2192 two-time, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Criticism_of_NASCAR"}
